 - Welcome and good evening, everyone.

3
00:00:09,840 --> 00:00:11,960
 Welcome to China Graduate School of Theology.

4
00:00:11,960 --> 00:00:13,160
 My name is Bernard Wong.

5
00:00:13,160 --> 00:00:17,040
 I'm the president here and also the host for tonight.

6
00:00:17,040 --> 00:00:19,440
 And before I begin, I'd like to let you know

7
00:00:19,440 --> 00:00:24,200
 that we have simultaneous interpretation by AI, right?

8
00:00:24,200 --> 00:00:26,560
 So we are catching up with technology here.

9
00:00:26,560 --> 00:00:28,080
 Let me switch to Chinese.

10
00:00:28,080 --> 00:00:32,000
 (speaking in foreign language)

11
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:47,760
 All right, let me switch back to English.

12
00:00:47,760 --> 00:00:51,880
 We are truly privileged to welcome

13
00:00:51,880 --> 00:00:54,960
 Reverend Dr. David Emmanuel Godley.

14
00:00:54,960 --> 00:00:57,000
 Dr. Godley serves as the president

15
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:01,400
 of Fuller Theological Seminary since 2023.

16
00:01:01,400 --> 00:01:03,680
 He's a distinguished theologian,

17
00:01:03,680 --> 00:01:07,440
 a globally recognized missiologist, and a seasoned leader.

18
00:01:07,440 --> 00:01:11,440
 Before his presidency at Fuller,

19
00:01:11,440 --> 00:01:14,600
 Dr. Godley served in many leadership capacities

20
00:01:14,600 --> 00:01:16,680
 at various institutions.

21
00:01:16,680 --> 00:01:18,720
 So to avoid taking up the whole evening,

22
00:01:18,720 --> 00:01:21,440
 I'll just give you two examples, all right?

23
00:01:21,440 --> 00:01:25,400
 He was the associate dean at Duke Divinity School,

24
00:01:25,400 --> 00:01:27,560
 and he led the Lord Cary Baptist

25
00:01:27,560 --> 00:01:29,680
 Foreign Mission Society for 20 years.

26
00:01:29,680 --> 00:01:33,760
 Having worked in over 35 countries,

27
00:01:33,760 --> 00:01:36,760
 Dr. Godley brings a vast global perspective

28
00:01:36,760 --> 00:01:39,480
 to the challenges of ministry.

29
00:01:39,480 --> 00:01:41,960
 He is not just an academic leader,

30
00:01:41,960 --> 00:01:45,400
 but a practitioner who has dedicated his life

31
00:01:45,400 --> 00:01:50,040
 to justice, advocacy, and equipping the global church

32
00:01:50,040 --> 00:01:51,640
 for faithful witness.

33
00:01:52,760 --> 00:01:55,720
 I have the privilege of meeting Dr. Godley in LA

34
00:01:55,720 --> 00:01:58,880
 when I visited Fuller in 2023.

35
00:01:58,880 --> 00:02:02,080
 Actually, it was soon after he became

36
00:02:02,080 --> 00:02:04,000
 the president of Fuller.

37
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:06,440
 So I'm very happy to meet him again here in Hong Kong

38
00:02:06,440 --> 00:02:08,240
 and welcome him here.

39
00:02:08,240 --> 00:02:10,720
 Actually, CGST and Fuller,

40
00:02:10,720 --> 00:02:14,840
 we have walked together in partnership for decades.

41
00:02:14,840 --> 00:02:16,880
 Our collaboration in joint programs

42
00:02:16,880 --> 00:02:19,960
 began as early as in the 1980s.

43
00:02:20,880 --> 00:02:24,520
 So we have formed a bridge of theological exchange

44
00:02:24,520 --> 00:02:27,080
 that has lasted for generations.

45
00:02:27,080 --> 00:02:28,120
 In more recent years,

46
00:02:28,120 --> 00:02:31,440
 we have been honored to host Dr. Godley's predecessor,

47
00:02:31,440 --> 00:02:34,520
 Dr. Mark Leberton, for some public lectures

48
00:02:34,520 --> 00:02:36,640
 in the previous several years.

49
00:02:36,640 --> 00:02:39,160
 And tonight, we are delighted to welcome Dr. Godley

50
00:02:39,160 --> 00:02:41,320
 into this ongoing partnership.

51
00:02:41,320 --> 00:02:44,880
 The theme for this evening is

52
00:02:44,880 --> 00:02:48,440
 Global Lessons for Leadership that Lasts.

53
00:02:48,440 --> 00:02:51,320
 The description for this lecture is as follows.

54
00:02:51,320 --> 00:02:55,520
 Christian leaders sometimes think of thriving in ministry

55
00:02:55,520 --> 00:02:58,760
 within the horizon of their personal participation

56
00:02:58,760 --> 00:03:01,080
 or their active service.

57
00:03:01,080 --> 00:03:04,040
 Because one's current Christian ministry

58
00:03:04,040 --> 00:03:06,800
 is connected to the past and the future,

59
00:03:06,800 --> 00:03:09,760
 we need to understand thriving in ways that live on

60
00:03:09,760 --> 00:03:13,120
 after our leadership assignments are completed

61
00:03:13,120 --> 00:03:15,080
 and life on earth is finished.

62
00:03:15,080 --> 00:03:17,680
 Drawing on his vast experience,

63
00:03:17,680 --> 00:03:20,880
 Dr. Godley will present a formula for flourishing

64
00:03:20,880 --> 00:03:23,320
 as a pathway to increase the probability

65
00:03:23,320 --> 00:03:25,200
 of thriving in ministry.

66
00:03:25,200 --> 00:03:29,040
 So for me personally, as a president of a seminary,

67
00:03:29,040 --> 00:03:31,920
 I very much look forward to the wisdom

68
00:03:31,920 --> 00:03:34,080
 that Dr. Godley will share with us tonight.

69
00:03:34,080 --> 00:03:37,880
 Following his lecture, we will have a response

70
00:03:37,880 --> 00:03:39,680
 from Reverend Dr. Michael Chu,

71
00:03:39,680 --> 00:03:43,120
 the vice president and chaplain of CJST.

72
00:03:43,120 --> 00:03:46,520
 And then we will have some time for question and answer.

73
00:03:46,520 --> 00:03:48,920
 So without further delay, please join me

74
00:03:48,920 --> 00:03:53,760
 in a very warm welcome for Reverend Dr. Emmanuel Godley.

75
00:03:53,760 --> 00:03:56,920
 (audience applauding)

76
00:03:56,920 --> 00:04:10,920
 - Thank you, President Wong.

77
00:04:10,920 --> 00:04:15,920
 And thank you to all of you for this opportunity

78
00:04:15,960 --> 00:04:17,160
 to be here today.

79
00:04:17,160 --> 00:04:22,080
 I'm honored to visit the campus

80
00:04:22,080 --> 00:04:24,360
 and to share in fellowship

81
00:04:24,360 --> 00:04:28,160
 and to know of the long history

82
00:04:28,160 --> 00:04:30,520
 that we've enjoyed over the years

83
00:04:30,520 --> 00:04:35,520
 and look forward to more history to be made together.

84
00:04:35,520 --> 00:04:44,720
 I'm also grateful to my colleague, Professor P.C. Loh,

85
00:04:45,840 --> 00:04:48,080
 who is a professor at Fuller Seminary

86
00:04:48,080 --> 00:04:53,080
 and the academic dean of our Chinese Studies Center.

87
00:04:53,080 --> 00:04:57,240
 And so I'm grateful for his partnership

88
00:04:57,240 --> 00:05:02,240
 and being a colleague together in education

89
00:05:02,240 --> 00:05:06,720
 and formation of Christian leaders.

90
00:05:06,720 --> 00:05:12,520
 So I'd like to talk with you today

91
00:05:12,520 --> 00:05:17,520
 about global lessons for leadership that lasts.

92
00:05:17,520 --> 00:05:24,480
 Christian leaders often measure thriving in ministry

93
00:05:24,480 --> 00:05:28,840
 within the limits of their own lifetime or active service.

94
00:05:28,840 --> 00:05:31,880
 It is natural to think this way.

95
00:05:31,880 --> 00:05:37,920
 We plan, we labor, we hope to see fruit while we are present.

96
00:05:40,040 --> 00:05:45,040
 Yet this horizon bounded by our personal participation

97
00:05:45,040 --> 00:05:49,920
 is far too small for the kind of leadership

98
00:05:49,920 --> 00:05:52,720
 to which God calls his people.

99
00:05:52,720 --> 00:05:58,280
 If ministry is truly God's work, and it is,

100
00:05:58,280 --> 00:06:03,280
 then its scope stretches far beyond our years,

101
00:06:03,280 --> 00:06:07,720
 our influence, and even our imagination.

102
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:12,080
 Leadership that lasts must therefore be rooted

103
00:06:12,080 --> 00:06:16,960
 in something deeper than personal success

104
00:06:16,960 --> 00:06:19,200
 or short-term outcomes.

105
00:06:19,200 --> 00:06:23,040
 In many leadership circles,

106
00:06:23,040 --> 00:06:26,320
 models and strategies developed in business

107
00:06:26,320 --> 00:06:30,880
 or organizational contexts are widely adopted.

108
00:06:30,880 --> 00:06:33,880
 These models can be helpful.

109
00:06:34,760 --> 00:06:39,280
 They offer structure, clarity, and tools for decision-making.

110
00:06:39,280 --> 00:06:44,360
 Concepts like vision casting, strategic planning,

111
00:06:44,360 --> 00:06:48,560
 and measurable outcomes provide leaders with ways

112
00:06:48,560 --> 00:06:53,560
 to organize their work and mobilize their teams.

113
00:06:53,560 --> 00:06:58,600
 However, while these frameworks are useful,

114
00:06:58,600 --> 00:07:03,760
 they are not sufficient for Christian leadership

115
00:07:03,760 --> 00:07:07,120
 because they are often built on assumptions

116
00:07:07,120 --> 00:07:11,480
 that do not fully align with the nature

117
00:07:11,480 --> 00:07:13,800
 of God's redemptive work.

118
00:07:13,800 --> 00:07:18,960
 Hear the words of 2 Corinthians chapter five,

119
00:07:18,960 --> 00:07:21,560
 beginning at verse 14.

120
00:07:21,560 --> 00:07:26,280
 For Christ's love compels us because we are convinced

121
00:07:26,280 --> 00:07:29,840
 that one died for all and therefore all died.

122
00:07:30,720 --> 00:07:34,480
 And he died for all that those who live

123
00:07:34,480 --> 00:07:37,560
 should no longer live for themselves,

124
00:07:37,560 --> 00:07:42,560
 but for him who died for them and was raised again.

125
00:07:42,560 --> 00:07:49,440
 So from now on, we regard no one

126
00:07:49,440 --> 00:07:51,960
 from a worldly point of view,

127
00:07:51,960 --> 00:07:55,920
 though we once regarded Christ in this way,

128
00:07:55,920 --> 00:07:58,720
 we do so no longer.

129
00:07:59,880 --> 00:08:04,840
 Therefore, if anyone is in Christ, the new creation has come.

130
00:08:04,840 --> 00:08:07,880
 The old is gone, the new is here.

131
00:08:07,880 --> 00:08:12,520
 All this is from God who reconciled us to himself

132
00:08:12,520 --> 00:08:17,520
 through Christ and gave us the ministry of reconciliation.

133
00:08:17,520 --> 00:08:22,080
 That God was reconciling the world to himself in Christ,

134
00:08:22,080 --> 00:08:25,280
 not counting people's sin against them.

135
00:08:25,280 --> 00:08:30,280
 And he has committed to us the message of reconciliation.

136
00:08:30,280 --> 00:08:35,280
 We are therefore Christ's ambassadors

137
00:08:35,280 --> 00:08:39,240
 as though God were making his appeal through us.

138
00:08:39,240 --> 00:08:44,240
 We implore you on Christ's behalf, be reconciled to God.

139
00:08:44,240 --> 00:08:48,680
 Our work as leaders is redemptive work.

140
00:08:48,680 --> 00:08:53,200
 Organizational vision is often defined

141
00:08:53,200 --> 00:08:57,280
 as what a leader or a team can see,

142
00:08:57,280 --> 00:09:00,640
 what they imagine is possible for the future.

143
00:09:00,640 --> 00:09:06,320
 It is shaped by creativity, ambition, and analysis.

144
00:09:06,320 --> 00:09:09,120
 In contrast, godly vision

145
00:09:09,120 --> 00:09:11,880
 is not primarily something we invent,

146
00:09:11,880 --> 00:09:14,960
 it is something we receive.

147
00:09:14,960 --> 00:09:18,720
 It is revealed rather than constructed.

148
00:09:19,720 --> 00:09:24,320
 Christian vision is divine revelation.

149
00:09:24,320 --> 00:09:27,200
 It is like going to a play

150
00:09:27,200 --> 00:09:29,800
 where the curtain is closed on the stage

151
00:09:29,800 --> 00:09:32,960
 where the production will occur.

152
00:09:32,960 --> 00:09:36,120
 At an appropriate time, the curtains are drawn back

153
00:09:36,120 --> 00:09:39,920
 so that you can witness the play being acted.

154
00:09:39,920 --> 00:09:43,160
 Without someone else pulling back the curtains,

155
00:09:43,160 --> 00:09:46,480
 you could not witness the play.

156
00:09:46,480 --> 00:09:51,480
 Similarly, without God drawing back the curtains,

157
00:09:51,480 --> 00:09:56,080
 you could not have a vision of what God desires.

158
00:09:56,080 --> 00:09:59,360
 Christian leaders are not simply visionaries

159
00:09:59,360 --> 00:10:02,480
 in the entrepreneurial sense.

160
00:10:02,480 --> 00:10:06,440
 They are discerners of divine direction.

161
00:10:06,440 --> 00:10:12,200
 They then steward what the Lord has given to them.

162
00:10:13,280 --> 00:10:17,600
 This means that discernment, prayer,

163
00:10:17,600 --> 00:10:21,000
 and attentiveness to God's voice

164
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:23,840
 are more central than innovation alone.

165
00:10:23,840 --> 00:10:27,880
 Similarly, organizational planning

166
00:10:27,880 --> 00:10:32,640
 tends to operate within defined time horizons.

167
00:10:32,640 --> 00:10:35,040
 Leaders are encouraged to think in terms

168
00:10:35,040 --> 00:10:38,560
 of long-range plans of 10 or more years,

169
00:10:38,560 --> 00:10:41,600
 strategic plans of three to five years,

170
00:10:41,600 --> 00:10:46,240
 and operational plans that focus on the immediate year.

171
00:10:46,240 --> 00:10:50,360
 These categories are practical and often necessary.

172
00:10:50,360 --> 00:10:54,560
 They help teams prioritize, allocate resources,

173
00:10:54,560 --> 00:10:55,920
 and measure progress.

174
00:10:55,920 --> 00:11:00,320
 Yet, even these well-structured timelines

175
00:11:00,320 --> 00:11:04,800
 fall short when applied to Christian ministry

176
00:11:04,800 --> 00:11:08,640
 without deeper theological reflection.

177
00:11:08,640 --> 00:11:10,640
 Why is this?

178
00:11:10,640 --> 00:11:13,240
 Because God's work is eternal.

179
00:11:13,240 --> 00:11:17,240
 The impact of ministry cannot always be measured

180
00:11:17,240 --> 00:11:21,520
 within a decade or even within a lifetime.

181
00:11:21,520 --> 00:11:26,520
 Scripture reminds us that one plants, another waters,

182
00:11:26,520 --> 00:11:30,520
 but God gives the increase.

183
00:11:30,520 --> 00:11:35,520
 And I reference 1 Corinthians 3, verse one through nine.

184
00:11:37,960 --> 00:11:41,520
 Again, one plants, another waters,

185
00:11:41,520 --> 00:11:44,800
 but God gives the increase.

186
00:11:44,800 --> 00:11:50,680
 This truth reframes how we think about success.

187
00:11:50,680 --> 00:11:56,440
 Faithfulness, not immediate results,

188
00:11:56,440 --> 00:11:58,760
 becomes the primary metric.

189
00:11:58,760 --> 00:12:04,760
 A leader may labor for years without seeing fruit,

190
00:12:04,760 --> 00:12:08,720
 yet their work may bear significant impact

191
00:12:08,720 --> 00:12:10,640
 in generations to come.

192
00:12:10,640 --> 00:12:15,240
 Conversely, rapid growth or visible success

193
00:12:15,240 --> 00:12:19,440
 in the short term does not necessarily indicate

194
00:12:19,440 --> 00:12:23,400
 lasting spiritual transformation.

195
00:12:23,400 --> 00:12:29,400
 This expanded perspective leads us to a crucial insight.

196
00:12:30,440 --> 00:12:35,440
 Christian ministry is always connected to both the past

197
00:12:35,440 --> 00:12:37,680
 and the future.

198
00:12:37,680 --> 00:12:42,520
 It is never an isolated endeavor.

199
00:12:42,520 --> 00:12:46,480
 We are part of something much larger than ourselves,

200
00:12:46,480 --> 00:12:51,480
 a living tradition that stretches across time and space.

201
00:12:51,480 --> 00:12:57,720
 First, we are part of the communion of saints.

202
00:12:58,360 --> 00:13:01,760
 This means that our ministry is not just alongside

203
00:13:01,760 --> 00:13:06,760
 those currently living, but also in continuity

204
00:13:06,760 --> 00:13:09,920
 with those who have gone before us.

205
00:13:09,920 --> 00:13:13,320
 The faith we proclaim, the scriptures we teach,

206
00:13:13,320 --> 00:13:15,400
 the practices we embody,

207
00:13:15,400 --> 00:13:20,040
 all of these have been handed down through generations.

208
00:13:20,040 --> 00:13:24,280
 We stand on the shoulders of faithful witnesses

209
00:13:24,280 --> 00:13:29,280
 who have preserved and transmitted the gospel

210
00:13:29,280 --> 00:13:34,200
 through centuries of challenge and change.

211
00:13:34,200 --> 00:13:39,200
 Second, we are stewards of legacies that we inherit.

212
00:13:39,200 --> 00:13:43,920
 Every ministry context comes with a history.

213
00:13:43,920 --> 00:13:48,760
 There are stories, sacrifices, victories,

214
00:13:48,760 --> 00:13:53,520
 and even failures that shape the present reality.

215
00:13:53,520 --> 00:13:56,960
 Wise leaders do not ignore this inheritance.

216
00:13:56,960 --> 00:13:59,800
 Instead, they seek to understand it,

217
00:13:59,800 --> 00:14:03,320
 to honor it, and to learn from it.

218
00:14:03,320 --> 00:14:06,240
 This requires humility.

219
00:14:06,240 --> 00:14:09,640
 It means recognizing that we are not the starting point

220
00:14:09,640 --> 00:14:14,640
 of the story, and that our role is not to erase the past,

221
00:14:14,640 --> 00:14:17,840
 but to build on it faithfully.

222
00:14:17,840 --> 00:14:21,720
 We all enter the stories of communities

223
00:14:21,720 --> 00:14:23,680
 that call us to serve.

224
00:14:23,680 --> 00:14:26,920
 Much happened before we arrived.

225
00:14:26,920 --> 00:14:29,800
 More will happen after we have left.

226
00:14:29,800 --> 00:14:32,240
 Our contributions are critical,

227
00:14:32,240 --> 00:14:35,680
 but they are only contributions.

228
00:14:35,680 --> 00:14:38,960
 Sometimes new leaders get frustrated

229
00:14:38,960 --> 00:14:42,080
 when the churches or ministries they come to serve

230
00:14:42,080 --> 00:14:47,080
 do not embrace their ideas immediately and enthusiastically.

231
00:14:47,080 --> 00:14:51,560
 But we all should remember that the only thing new

232
00:14:51,560 --> 00:14:56,560
 is you, and that the congregations and communities we serve

233
00:14:56,560 --> 00:15:01,880
 have been on a journey, and our task as leaders

234
00:15:01,880 --> 00:15:05,480
 is to steward well the legacies that we inherit.

235
00:15:05,480 --> 00:15:10,440
 So first, we are part of the community in a sense.

236
00:15:10,440 --> 00:15:13,760
 Second, we are stewards of legacies we inherit.

237
00:15:13,760 --> 00:15:17,040
 And third, we are stewards of ministries

238
00:15:17,040 --> 00:15:20,200
 that we will eventually hand off to others.

239
00:15:21,480 --> 00:15:26,480
 Leadership is temporary, even when it spans decades.

240
00:15:26,480 --> 00:15:29,160
 My father, of blessed memory,

241
00:15:29,160 --> 00:15:34,160
 served as the pastor of one congregation for 47 years.

242
00:15:34,160 --> 00:15:36,680
 By the time of his retirement,

243
00:15:36,680 --> 00:15:41,680
 very few people had any, I'm sorry,

244
00:15:41,680 --> 00:15:46,720
 very few people had any recollection of his predecessor.

245
00:15:48,640 --> 00:15:51,920
 There are now people in that church

246
00:15:51,920 --> 00:15:54,280
 who only knew his leadership.

247
00:15:54,280 --> 00:15:58,840
 Like runners in a relay race,

248
00:15:58,840 --> 00:16:03,120
 we receive the baton and we hand it off to another.

249
00:16:03,120 --> 00:16:09,240
 There will come a time when every leader steps aside,

250
00:16:09,240 --> 00:16:13,280
 whether by transition, or retirement, or death.

251
00:16:14,240 --> 00:16:18,720
 The question then is not only what we accomplish,

252
00:16:18,720 --> 00:16:20,640
 but what we leave behind.

253
00:16:20,640 --> 00:16:23,200
 Have we developed others?

254
00:16:23,200 --> 00:16:26,600
 Have we created systems and cultures that can endure?

255
00:16:26,600 --> 00:16:28,960
 Have we prepared the next generation

256
00:16:28,960 --> 00:16:32,320
 to carry the ministry forward?

257
00:16:32,320 --> 00:16:37,320
 Sometimes very few people will fully appreciate our labor,

258
00:16:37,320 --> 00:16:42,520
 but God sees, and God knows.

259
00:16:43,680 --> 00:16:46,040
 These realities challenge us

260
00:16:46,040 --> 00:16:49,560
 to rethink how we understand leadership.

261
00:16:49,560 --> 00:16:52,960
 It is not enough to ask, what did I achieve?

262
00:16:52,960 --> 00:16:58,920
 We must also ask, what will endure after I'm gone?

263
00:16:58,920 --> 00:17:04,600
 This shift moves us from a focus on personal legacy

264
00:17:04,600 --> 00:17:09,600
 to a focus on faithful stewardship within God's larger story.

265
00:17:10,920 --> 00:17:14,240
 To cultivate this kind of enduring leadership,

266
00:17:14,240 --> 00:17:17,920
 it is helpful to reflect on the ministries and leaders

267
00:17:17,920 --> 00:17:20,920
 who have already inspired us.

268
00:17:20,920 --> 00:17:24,280
 What is it about their lives that continues to speak,

269
00:17:24,280 --> 00:17:27,560
 even after their service has ended?

270
00:17:27,560 --> 00:17:32,400
 Often, it is not merely their accomplishments,

271
00:17:32,400 --> 00:17:36,240
 but their faithfulness, their character,

272
00:17:36,240 --> 00:17:39,560
 and their alignment with God's purposes.

273
00:17:39,560 --> 00:17:42,040
 Their influence persists

274
00:17:42,040 --> 00:17:45,520
 because it was rooted in something deeper

275
00:17:45,520 --> 00:17:48,120
 than immediate results.

276
00:17:48,120 --> 00:17:51,800
 Here, the Akan philosophy of Sankofa

277
00:17:51,800 --> 00:17:55,040
 offers a powerful insight.

278
00:17:55,040 --> 00:18:00,240
 Sankofa teaches us to, quote,

279
00:18:00,240 --> 00:18:03,520
 "Go back and get it," end quote.

280
00:18:03,520 --> 00:18:08,240
 It teaches us to retrieve from the past

281
00:18:08,240 --> 00:18:11,600
 what is necessary for moving forward.

282
00:18:11,600 --> 00:18:13,600
 This is not about nostalgia

283
00:18:13,600 --> 00:18:17,400
 or romanticized recollections of history.

284
00:18:17,400 --> 00:18:21,360
 Rather, it is about discerning what is valuable,

285
00:18:21,360 --> 00:18:24,360
 enduring, and instructive.

286
00:18:24,360 --> 00:18:28,040
 For Christian leaders, this means engaging deeply

287
00:18:28,040 --> 00:18:30,560
 with the history of the church,

288
00:18:30,560 --> 00:18:32,160
 learning from its wisdom,

289
00:18:32,160 --> 00:18:37,160
 and allowing it to inform our present practice.

290
00:18:37,480 --> 00:18:41,720
 In a world that often prizes novelty and innovation,

291
00:18:41,720 --> 00:18:44,840
 Sankofa reminds us that progress

292
00:18:44,840 --> 00:18:49,240
 is not always about creating something new.

293
00:18:49,240 --> 00:18:53,920
 Many of us inhabit the cultural curation

294
00:18:53,920 --> 00:18:56,240
 of Western societies,

295
00:18:56,240 --> 00:18:58,680
 and we are seduced to thinking

296
00:18:58,680 --> 00:19:02,040
 that what is new is improved.

297
00:19:02,040 --> 00:19:04,720
 There are many things, however,

298
00:19:04,720 --> 00:19:07,840
 that are old and still good.

299
00:19:07,840 --> 00:19:10,680
 Think of faith.

300
00:19:10,680 --> 00:19:12,400
 Think of hope.

301
00:19:12,400 --> 00:19:14,360
 Think of love.

302
00:19:14,360 --> 00:19:17,440
 They're old, and they're good.

303
00:19:17,440 --> 00:19:22,920
 The 1913 hymn by George Bernard

304
00:19:22,920 --> 00:19:25,600
 that is very popular in the United States

305
00:19:25,600 --> 00:19:26,920
 says it this way.

306
00:19:26,920 --> 00:19:31,640
 "On a hill far away stood an old rugged cross,

307
00:19:31,640 --> 00:19:34,840
 "the emblem of suffering and shame.

308
00:19:34,840 --> 00:19:37,280
 "And I love that old cross

309
00:19:37,280 --> 00:19:39,000
 "where the dearest and best

310
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:42,320
 "for a world of lost sinners was slain.

311
00:19:42,320 --> 00:19:46,360
 "So I'll cherish the old rugged cross

312
00:19:46,360 --> 00:19:49,680
 "till my trophies at last I lay down.

313
00:19:49,680 --> 00:19:54,120
 "I will cling to the old rugged cross

314
00:19:54,120 --> 00:19:58,440
 "and exchange it someday for a crown."

315
00:19:59,480 --> 00:20:04,480
 Sometimes leadership is about recovering

316
00:20:04,480 --> 00:20:08,040
 what has been forgotten or neglected.

317
00:20:08,040 --> 00:20:13,040
 Practices such as prayer, discipleship,

318
00:20:13,040 --> 00:20:16,560
 community life, and theological reflection

319
00:20:16,560 --> 00:20:20,440
 have sustained the church for centuries.

320
00:20:20,440 --> 00:20:25,440
 When these are rediscovered and faithfully practiced,

321
00:20:25,480 --> 00:20:30,120
 they provide a foundation for lasting impact.

322
00:20:30,120 --> 00:20:33,960
 This perspective aligns with the idea

323
00:20:33,960 --> 00:20:38,960
 that historic Christianity is not just a set of beliefs,

324
00:20:38,960 --> 00:20:45,040
 but, quote, "The story of everything,

325
00:20:45,040 --> 00:20:48,320
 "the human and institutions," end quote.

326
00:20:48,320 --> 00:20:52,360
 And I'm quoting the scholar Kevin Rowe

327
00:20:52,360 --> 00:20:56,040
 from his book "Christianity Surprise."

328
00:20:56,040 --> 00:20:59,440
 He goes on to say, "This story provides an anchor

329
00:20:59,440 --> 00:21:01,520
 "for our ministry and leadership.

330
00:21:01,520 --> 00:21:05,160
 "It situates our work within a grand narrative

331
00:21:05,160 --> 00:21:08,600
 "that includes creation, redemption, and restoration.

332
00:21:08,600 --> 00:21:11,600
 "It reminds us that our efforts

333
00:21:11,600 --> 00:21:16,000
 "are part of God's ongoing work in the world."

334
00:21:17,560 --> 00:21:22,560
 When leaders see themselves within the larger story,

335
00:21:22,560 --> 00:21:25,600
 our priorities begin to shift.

336
00:21:25,600 --> 00:21:29,560
 Short-term gains become less compelling

337
00:21:29,560 --> 00:21:32,600
 than long-term faithfulness.

338
00:21:32,600 --> 00:21:35,800
 Personal recognition becomes less important

339
00:21:35,800 --> 00:21:38,400
 than collective continuity.

340
00:21:38,400 --> 00:21:44,360
 Innovation is not pursued for its own sake,

341
00:21:44,560 --> 00:21:48,400
 but in service to enduring truth.

342
00:21:48,400 --> 00:21:52,040
 Ultimately, leadership that lasts

343
00:21:52,040 --> 00:21:55,440
 is shaped by a posture of stewardship.

344
00:21:55,440 --> 00:21:59,160
 We receive from those who came before us,

345
00:21:59,160 --> 00:22:02,400
 we faithfully tend to what has been entrusted to us,

346
00:22:02,400 --> 00:22:07,400
 and we prepare to pass on to those who will come after us.

347
00:22:07,400 --> 00:22:10,640
 This requires patience, humility,

348
00:22:10,640 --> 00:22:14,000
 and trust in God's sovereignty.

349
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:19,000
 Our lives and our leadership are in God's hands.

350
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:25,360
 It also requires a redefinition of success.

351
00:22:25,360 --> 00:22:28,240
 Success is not measured by how much we accomplish

352
00:22:28,240 --> 00:22:30,680
 within our limited time frame,

353
00:22:30,680 --> 00:22:33,280
 but how faithfully we participate

354
00:22:33,280 --> 00:22:35,480
 in God's eternal purposes.

355
00:22:35,480 --> 00:22:38,200
 Leadership should be measured

356
00:22:38,200 --> 00:22:42,120
 by whether our efforts contribute to something

357
00:22:42,120 --> 00:22:46,440
 that will continue to bear fruit long after we are gone.

358
00:22:46,440 --> 00:22:50,800
 This kind of leadership is not about accumulation

359
00:22:50,800 --> 00:22:53,400
 of recognition and resources.

360
00:22:53,400 --> 00:22:58,040
 Instead, it is about distribution so that none go without,

361
00:22:58,040 --> 00:23:00,560
 and that we participate in the future

362
00:23:00,560 --> 00:23:03,520
 by what we contribute in the present.

363
00:23:03,520 --> 00:23:07,360
 In this way, Christian leadership becomes less

364
00:23:07,360 --> 00:23:09,640
 about building our own vision

365
00:23:09,640 --> 00:23:12,160
 and more about aligning with the revelation

366
00:23:12,160 --> 00:23:14,080
 of the Holy Spirit.

367
00:23:14,080 --> 00:23:19,080
 God's vision, revelation, spans across eras

368
00:23:19,080 --> 00:23:24,680
 and culminates in his ultimate redemption of all things.

369
00:23:24,680 --> 00:23:28,840
 When leaders embrace this perspective,

370
00:23:28,840 --> 00:23:33,840
 they are freed from the pressure of immediate results

371
00:23:33,840 --> 00:23:37,560
 and empowered to lead with courage,

372
00:23:37,560 --> 00:23:40,480
 clarity, and compassion.

373
00:23:40,480 --> 00:23:45,480
 They press on with faith, hope, and love.

374
00:23:45,480 --> 00:23:50,440
 Such leadership does not end when a position is relinquished

375
00:23:50,440 --> 00:23:53,400
 or when life on earth is finished.

376
00:23:53,400 --> 00:23:58,400
 It echoes into the future, carried forward by those

377
00:23:58,400 --> 00:24:01,120
 who have been shaped, equipped,

378
00:24:01,120 --> 00:24:04,520
 and inspired to continue the work.

379
00:24:04,520 --> 00:24:08,520
 And in that sense, it truly lasts.

380
00:24:08,520 --> 00:24:12,760
 I'd like to say a word now about the value

381
00:24:12,760 --> 00:24:17,760
 of a vibrant variety of voices for leadership lessons.

382
00:24:17,760 --> 00:24:25,960
 Beyond the many models from the North Atlantic West

383
00:24:25,960 --> 00:24:30,960
 about ministry leadership are important lessons

384
00:24:31,000 --> 00:24:35,920
 that exceed or enrich those insights.

385
00:24:35,920 --> 00:24:40,920
 With less than 11% of Christians in the North Atlantic West,

386
00:24:40,920 --> 00:24:45,840
 we need to learn more from believers globally.

387
00:24:45,840 --> 00:24:49,760
 A challenge for the church is to engage

388
00:24:49,760 --> 00:24:53,000
 with mutuality and reciprocity,

389
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:56,680
 the institutional and financial weight of the church

390
00:24:56,680 --> 00:25:01,120
 informed by the Western world with the numeric

391
00:25:01,120 --> 00:25:05,600
 and dynamic breadth of a church in the majority world.

392
00:25:05,600 --> 00:25:12,040
 What voices do we need for learning leadership lessons?

393
00:25:12,040 --> 00:25:19,520
 The Nigerian author, Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie,

394
00:25:19,520 --> 00:25:24,960
 has a famous TED Talk recorded in 2009 entitled

395
00:25:26,600 --> 00:25:30,360
 The Danger of a Single Story.

396
00:25:30,360 --> 00:25:36,840
 In this talk, she shares about how relying on single stories

397
00:25:36,840 --> 00:25:42,320
 reduces people to incomplete stereotypes.

398
00:25:42,320 --> 00:25:45,400
 It takes away their dignity.

399
00:25:45,400 --> 00:25:50,240
 It contributes to misunderstanding people,

400
00:25:50,240 --> 00:25:54,840
 and it becomes a tool for those who have power

401
00:25:54,840 --> 00:25:58,120
 to preserve their places of privilege

402
00:25:58,120 --> 00:26:02,080
 by defining the realities of others.

403
00:26:02,080 --> 00:26:08,560
 We need to embrace the many stories of people, lives,

404
00:26:08,560 --> 00:26:14,400
 churches, context, and communities to be good leaders.

405
00:26:14,400 --> 00:26:20,600
 Far too often, leadership studies generally,

406
00:26:20,600 --> 00:26:25,480
 as well as leadership studies in theological, ecclesial,

407
00:26:25,480 --> 00:26:28,240
 and organizational settings,

408
00:26:28,240 --> 00:26:33,000
 rely too heavily on insights, books, thought leaders,

409
00:26:33,000 --> 00:26:38,000
 podcasts, and the like produced from places of privilege

410
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:43,240
 and for places of privilege in the North Atlantic West.

411
00:26:43,240 --> 00:26:48,560
 In other words, there is a reliance upon a single story

412
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:52,560
 created from and for those who live in

413
00:26:52,560 --> 00:26:57,360
 and rely on the cultural curations of the West.

414
00:26:57,360 --> 00:27:03,600
 I once had Asian and Latin American students tell me

415
00:27:03,600 --> 00:27:06,280
 that they were so emotionally impacted

416
00:27:06,280 --> 00:27:10,560
 by receiving my syllabus with required resources

417
00:27:10,560 --> 00:27:13,680
 from their cultural perspectives

418
00:27:13,680 --> 00:27:17,720
 that they went and hid themselves to cry.

419
00:27:19,480 --> 00:27:20,920
 They had gotten all the way

420
00:27:20,920 --> 00:27:24,920
 through their educational experiences in the United States

421
00:27:24,920 --> 00:27:27,000
 to their doctoral studies

422
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:29,640
 before they had experienced courses

423
00:27:29,640 --> 00:27:34,320
 with required resources from their cultural contexts.

424
00:27:34,320 --> 00:27:37,440
 The realities of the institutional

425
00:27:37,440 --> 00:27:40,480
 and financial strength of Western cultures

426
00:27:40,480 --> 00:27:45,480
 result in an over-reliance of single story syndrome.

427
00:27:47,140 --> 00:27:50,360
 This impoverishes the theological, intellectual,

428
00:27:50,360 --> 00:27:53,320
 and ecclesial experiences of the church.

429
00:27:53,320 --> 00:27:59,480
 I want to share tonight with you some leadership insights

430
00:27:59,480 --> 00:28:03,320
 from my missiological studies from partners connected

431
00:28:03,320 --> 00:28:07,240
 with the Locke Carey Baptist Foreign Mission Society

432
00:28:07,240 --> 00:28:10,440
 for 50 years or more.

433
00:28:10,440 --> 00:28:13,400
 My missiological research gave me insights

434
00:28:13,400 --> 00:28:17,220
 on leadership lessons for longevity of impact

435
00:28:17,220 --> 00:28:22,220
 from partners in Liberia, India, Nigeria, and Guyana,

436
00:28:22,220 --> 00:28:28,600
 from Africa, Asia, and South America.

437
00:28:28,600 --> 00:28:33,760
 The history of the Locke Carey Foreign Mission Society

438
00:28:33,760 --> 00:28:38,360
 offers more than a narrative of missionary activity.

439
00:28:38,360 --> 00:28:40,200
 It provides a rich case study

440
00:28:40,200 --> 00:28:44,560
 in leadership shaped by faith, adversity,

441
00:28:44,560 --> 00:28:47,980
 cultural complexity, and long-term vision.

442
00:28:47,980 --> 00:28:51,080
 Across generations,

443
00:28:51,080 --> 00:28:54,600
 leaders navigated political instability,

444
00:28:54,600 --> 00:28:58,680
 financial hardship, cross-cultural dynamics,

445
00:28:58,680 --> 00:29:03,020
 and institutional development.

446
00:29:03,020 --> 00:29:08,940
 From this context emerge enduring leadership lessons

447
00:29:09,540 --> 00:29:12,640
 that remain relevant for leaders in ministry,

448
00:29:12,640 --> 00:29:16,400
 education, and global engagement today.

449
00:29:16,400 --> 00:29:19,000
 So I'm going to share with you some insights

450
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:23,440
 from these contexts and these insights about leadership

451
00:29:23,440 --> 00:29:27,120
 primarily that do not make reference

452
00:29:27,120 --> 00:29:29,640
 to the North Atlantic West.

453
00:29:29,640 --> 00:29:31,080
 Now I do want to share with you,

454
00:29:31,080 --> 00:29:34,760
 and Professor Lowe thought that you would be interested,

455
00:29:34,760 --> 00:29:37,840
 I served as the leader of the Locke Carey Society

456
00:29:37,840 --> 00:29:41,280
 for 22 years, and in the 19,

457
00:29:41,280 --> 00:29:46,280
 this is a historic African-American global mission society

458
00:29:46,280 --> 00:29:49,480
 founded in 1897.

459
00:29:49,480 --> 00:29:52,880
 In the 1940s,

460
00:29:52,880 --> 00:29:56,160
 this historic African-American mission society

461
00:29:56,160 --> 00:29:59,220
 was working with Chinese Christians

462
00:29:59,220 --> 00:30:04,220
 to co-create an educational institution in the 1940s.

463
00:30:05,160 --> 00:30:08,020
 But because of the political dynamics

464
00:30:08,020 --> 00:30:10,500
 that was brought to a halt,

465
00:30:10,500 --> 00:30:14,400
 and that was a interesting personal connection

466
00:30:14,400 --> 00:30:16,540
 with my coming to this part of the world.

467
00:30:16,540 --> 00:30:20,080
 I'm going to share with you some leadership lessons

468
00:30:20,080 --> 00:30:22,780
 from the Locke Carey Mission in Liberia,

469
00:30:22,780 --> 00:30:25,500
 which was established in 1908.

470
00:30:25,500 --> 00:30:29,500
 One of the most significant lessons

471
00:30:30,500 --> 00:30:35,500
 is the importance of leadership rooted in conviction.

472
00:30:35,500 --> 00:30:41,520
 The early pioneers of African-American missions to Africa

473
00:30:41,520 --> 00:30:43,760
 embraced a mission

474
00:30:43,760 --> 00:30:46,700
 that was both controversial and uncertain.

475
00:30:46,700 --> 00:30:51,520
 While the American colonization society's efforts

476
00:30:51,520 --> 00:30:55,800
 were widely debated, people like the Reverend Locke Carey,

477
00:30:55,800 --> 00:30:59,680
 who was born enslaved in 1780,

478
00:30:59,680 --> 00:31:03,000
 made his profession of faith in 1807,

479
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:08,400
 purchased his and his family's freedom in 1813,

480
00:31:08,400 --> 00:31:10,840
 and led the first Baptist missionaries

481
00:31:10,840 --> 00:31:15,400
 to go to Africa from the United States in 1821.

482
00:31:15,400 --> 00:31:19,360
 This Reverend Locke Carey and others

483
00:31:19,360 --> 00:31:23,300
 discerned a calling beyond the politics of the moment.

484
00:31:23,300 --> 00:31:28,400
 Their leadership was not reactive to public opinion,

485
00:31:28,400 --> 00:31:32,760
 but anchored in a clear sense of divine purpose.

486
00:31:32,760 --> 00:31:36,200
 This kind of leadership requires courage,

487
00:31:36,200 --> 00:31:39,200
 the willingness to act decisively,

488
00:31:39,200 --> 00:31:43,920
 even when the path forward is contested or unclear.

489
00:31:43,920 --> 00:31:49,200
 Now, closely related to leadership rooted in conviction

490
00:31:49,200 --> 00:31:54,960
 is the integration of proclamation and practice.

491
00:31:54,960 --> 00:31:58,800
 From its earliest days, the mission in Liberia

492
00:31:58,800 --> 00:32:02,260
 rejected a narrow understanding of ministry.

493
00:32:02,260 --> 00:32:05,960
 Leaders recognized that preaching the gospel

494
00:32:05,960 --> 00:32:10,960
 must be accompanied by tangible investment in people's lives.

495
00:32:10,960 --> 00:32:15,920
 This led to the development of schools,

496
00:32:15,920 --> 00:32:20,920
 vocational training programs, and community initiatives.

497
00:32:21,160 --> 00:32:25,360
 Leaders such as Reverend William H. Thomas

498
00:32:25,360 --> 00:32:30,360
 and his wife Cora Thomas served from 1908 to 1943.

499
00:32:30,360 --> 00:32:36,320
 They embodied this integrated vision

500
00:32:36,320 --> 00:32:41,320
 and emphasized character, industry, and scholarship.

501
00:32:41,320 --> 00:32:46,200
 Their work demonstrates that effective leadership

502
00:32:46,200 --> 00:32:51,200
 addresses the whole person spiritually, intellectually,

503
00:32:51,200 --> 00:32:55,740
 and practically.

504
00:32:55,740 --> 00:33:00,000
 Visionary leaders do not separate belief from action.

505
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:02,640
 They bring them together

506
00:33:02,640 --> 00:33:05,460
 in meaningful and sustainable ways.

507
00:33:05,460 --> 00:33:09,520
 Another critical lesson is resilience

508
00:33:09,520 --> 00:33:12,000
 in the face of persistent adversity.

509
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:13,840
 Throughout its history,

510
00:33:13,840 --> 00:33:16,760
 the mission encountered financial constraints,

511
00:33:16,760 --> 00:33:21,760
 global economic downturns, and systemic inequalities.

512
00:33:21,760 --> 00:33:26,080
 These challenges were compounded by world events

513
00:33:26,080 --> 00:33:31,080
 such as the World Wars, World War I and World War II,

514
00:33:31,080 --> 00:33:34,160
 the Great Depression, and more.

515
00:33:34,160 --> 00:33:37,840
 Yet, despite all of these challenges,

516
00:33:37,840 --> 00:33:40,820
 leaders did not abandon their mission.

517
00:33:40,820 --> 00:33:45,820
 Instead, they adapted, persevered, and continued to build.

518
00:33:45,820 --> 00:33:50,640
 This resilience was not just endurance.

519
00:33:50,640 --> 00:33:55,120
 It was an active, creative response to difficulty.

520
00:33:55,120 --> 00:33:58,320
 Leaders learned to do more with less,

521
00:33:58,320 --> 00:34:01,800
 to prioritize wisely, and to remain faithful

522
00:34:01,800 --> 00:34:05,620
 even when progress was slow or uncertain.

523
00:34:05,620 --> 00:34:09,200
 The mission also highlights the importance

524
00:34:09,200 --> 00:34:14,200
 of adaptive leadership in changing contexts.

525
00:34:14,200 --> 00:34:19,040
 For example, Reverend A. Wesley Knott recognized

526
00:34:19,040 --> 00:34:23,240
 that Africa was undergoing rapid transformation

527
00:34:23,240 --> 00:34:28,080
 and that mission strategies needed to evolve accordingly.

528
00:34:28,080 --> 00:34:31,640
 He advocated for incorporating scientific

529
00:34:31,640 --> 00:34:36,640
 and technical education alongside spiritual formation.

530
00:34:37,560 --> 00:34:40,240
 This forward-thinking approach

531
00:34:40,240 --> 00:34:43,460
 demonstrates a key leadership principle.

532
00:34:43,460 --> 00:34:48,460
 Methods must change even when the mission is constant.

533
00:34:48,460 --> 00:34:52,560
 Effective leaders pay attention

534
00:34:52,560 --> 00:34:56,480
 to cultural, technological, and societal shifts

535
00:34:56,480 --> 00:35:01,280
 and adjust their strategies to remain impactful.

536
00:35:01,280 --> 00:35:06,360
 Another central theme throughout the mission's history

537
00:35:06,360 --> 00:35:09,960
 is the value of developing local leadership

538
00:35:09,960 --> 00:35:11,880
 and fostering partnership.

539
00:35:11,880 --> 00:35:16,120
 Early missionaries gradually recognized

540
00:35:16,120 --> 00:35:18,520
 that sustainable impact required

541
00:35:18,520 --> 00:35:22,120
 empowering indigenous leaders,

542
00:35:22,120 --> 00:35:26,720
 and this shift from dependency to partnership was crucial.

543
00:35:26,720 --> 00:35:32,560
 By investing in education and leadership development,

544
00:35:32,560 --> 00:35:36,760
 the mission enabled Liberians to take ownership

545
00:35:36,760 --> 00:35:40,720
 of their own institutions and communities.

546
00:35:40,720 --> 00:35:45,720
 The rise of figures like Ambassador Angie Brooks Randolph,

547
00:35:45,720 --> 00:35:50,200
 who prior to her diplomatic career was a principal

548
00:35:50,200 --> 00:35:53,280
 at the Lottery Mission School in Brewerville

549
00:35:53,280 --> 00:35:57,080
 symbolizes this approach.

550
00:35:57,080 --> 00:36:02,440
 Angie Brooks Randolph was a Liberian diplomat

551
00:36:02,440 --> 00:36:04,000
 and jurist.

552
00:36:04,000 --> 00:36:07,640
 She was the first African female president

553
00:36:07,640 --> 00:36:10,280
 of the United Nations General Assembly

554
00:36:10,280 --> 00:36:14,800
 elected in September of 1969,

555
00:36:14,800 --> 00:36:17,360
 and she was also the second woman

556
00:36:17,360 --> 00:36:22,120
 from any nation to head a UN body.

557
00:36:22,120 --> 00:36:26,160
 She later was appointed an associate justice

558
00:36:26,160 --> 00:36:28,560
 of the Supreme Court of Liberia

559
00:36:28,560 --> 00:36:33,560
 and became the first woman to serve on Liberia's Supreme Court.

560
00:36:33,560 --> 00:36:39,200
 This is an example of indigenous leadership

561
00:36:39,200 --> 00:36:42,800
 that serves a broad context.

562
00:36:42,800 --> 00:36:46,760
 Leadership that lasts is not about maintaining control,

563
00:36:46,760 --> 00:36:50,040
 but about equipping others to lead.

564
00:36:50,040 --> 00:36:52,080
 It requires humility, trust,

565
00:36:52,080 --> 00:36:55,480
 and a commitment to shared responsibility.

566
00:36:56,760 --> 00:36:59,520
 The story of Liberia also underscores

567
00:36:59,520 --> 00:37:02,200
 the transformative power of relational

568
00:37:02,200 --> 00:37:04,880
 and cross-cultural leadership.

569
00:37:04,880 --> 00:37:08,880
 Missionaries who immerse themselves in Liberian society

570
00:37:08,880 --> 00:37:12,360
 often experience a shift in perspective.

571
00:37:12,360 --> 00:37:15,960
 They move from seeing themselves

572
00:37:15,960 --> 00:37:19,520
 as outsiders bringing solutions

573
00:37:19,520 --> 00:37:24,520
 to recognizing mutual dignity and shared humanity.

574
00:37:25,840 --> 00:37:29,920
 Leaders like Reverend Samuel Ray exemplified this change,

575
00:37:29,920 --> 00:37:34,400
 emphasizing relationships over hierarchy.

576
00:37:34,400 --> 00:37:39,400
 This lesson is especially relevant in a globalized world.

577
00:37:39,400 --> 00:37:42,840
 Effective leadership across cultures

578
00:37:42,840 --> 00:37:47,600
 requires listening, learning, and genuine respect.

579
00:37:47,600 --> 00:37:50,720
 Another profound lesson emerges

580
00:37:50,720 --> 00:37:55,120
 from the missions experienced during Liberia's Civil War.

581
00:37:56,360 --> 00:37:59,240
 And that is leadership in crisis

582
00:37:59,240 --> 00:38:02,200
 demands courage and compassion.

583
00:38:02,200 --> 00:38:05,560
 Under extreme conditions of violence,

584
00:38:05,560 --> 00:38:08,440
 displacement, and institutional collapse,

585
00:38:08,440 --> 00:38:11,960
 leaders such as Jeremiah Winslow Walker

586
00:38:11,960 --> 00:38:15,520
 made difficult decisions to keep the mission alive.

587
00:38:15,520 --> 00:38:18,240
 Reopening schools during conflict

588
00:38:18,240 --> 00:38:21,840
 was not merely an administrative act.

589
00:38:21,840 --> 00:38:24,680
 It was a statement of hope.

590
00:38:24,680 --> 00:38:28,840
 These actions highlight that in times of crisis,

591
00:38:28,840 --> 00:38:32,520
 leadership is not just about survival,

592
00:38:32,520 --> 00:38:36,840
 but about providing stability, vision,

593
00:38:36,840 --> 00:38:40,120
 and care for those most affected.

594
00:38:40,120 --> 00:38:43,640
 In the post-war period, the mission demonstrated

595
00:38:43,640 --> 00:38:46,280
 the importance of holistic restoration

596
00:38:46,280 --> 00:38:48,320
 and forward-looking leadership.

597
00:38:48,320 --> 00:38:52,520
 Leaders expanded their focus to include trauma healing,

598
00:38:52,520 --> 00:38:55,280
 reintegration of former child soldiers,

599
00:38:55,280 --> 00:38:56,720
 healthcare initiatives,

600
00:38:56,720 --> 00:38:59,800
 and support for vulnerable populations.

601
00:38:59,800 --> 00:39:02,200
 This reflects an understanding that leadership

602
00:39:02,200 --> 00:39:06,760
 must respond to the full scope of human need,

603
00:39:06,760 --> 00:39:10,720
 especially in context of deep brokenness.

604
00:39:10,720 --> 00:39:15,640
 It also shows the importance of long-term thinking,

605
00:39:15,640 --> 00:39:20,640
 rebuilding not just structures, but lives and community.

606
00:39:21,840 --> 00:39:24,760
 Finally, the enduring legacy of the Lottery Mission

607
00:39:24,760 --> 00:39:29,760
 in Liberia points to the necessity of sustained commitment

608
00:39:29,760 --> 00:39:32,280
 and generational thinking.

609
00:39:32,280 --> 00:39:37,040
 No single leader accomplished all that the mission achieved.

610
00:39:37,040 --> 00:39:40,240
 Instead, progress unfolded over decades

611
00:39:40,240 --> 00:39:43,040
 through the contributions of many individuals.

612
00:39:43,040 --> 00:39:46,080
 Each leader built upon the work of their predecessors

613
00:39:46,080 --> 00:39:48,240
 while preparing the way for those

614
00:39:48,240 --> 00:39:50,960
 who would be their successors.

615
00:39:50,960 --> 00:39:55,960
 This long view challenges leaders

616
00:39:55,960 --> 00:39:59,160
 to think beyond immediate results

617
00:39:59,160 --> 00:40:02,760
 and consider the lasting impact of their decisions.

618
00:40:02,760 --> 00:40:05,600
 In conclusion, about Liberia,

619
00:40:05,600 --> 00:40:09,840
 the leadership lessons from Lottery Mission in Liberia

620
00:40:09,840 --> 00:40:12,160
 are practical and profound.

621
00:40:12,160 --> 00:40:15,080
 They call for leaders to anchor their work and purpose,

622
00:40:15,080 --> 00:40:17,000
 integrate vision with action,

623
00:40:17,000 --> 00:40:21,560
 remain resilient in adversity, adapt to changing contexts,

624
00:40:21,560 --> 00:40:25,680
 empower others, lead relationally across cultures,

625
00:40:25,680 --> 00:40:27,760
 act courageously in crisis,

626
00:40:27,760 --> 00:40:31,760
 and commit to long-term generational impact.

627
00:40:31,760 --> 00:40:34,000
 These lessons remind us that leadership

628
00:40:34,000 --> 00:40:37,360
 is not merely about achieving goals,

629
00:40:37,360 --> 00:40:40,520
 but about faithfully stewarding a mission

630
00:40:40,520 --> 00:40:44,640
 that extends far beyond any single lifetime.

631
00:40:45,720 --> 00:40:49,000
 I'd like to share a few insights of leadership lessons

632
00:40:49,000 --> 00:40:51,720
 from the Lottery Mission in India.

633
00:40:51,720 --> 00:40:58,120
 This sustained partnership, it started in the 1930s,

634
00:40:58,120 --> 00:41:01,440
 discontinued and then picked up in 1947

635
00:41:01,440 --> 00:41:03,040
 and continues to today.

636
00:41:03,040 --> 00:41:08,800
 The history of the Lottery Society in India

637
00:41:08,800 --> 00:41:11,640
 is a compelling window into leadership

638
00:41:11,640 --> 00:41:16,000
 by cross-cultural engagement, endurance,

639
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:20,320
 and long-term commitment to transformation.

640
00:41:20,320 --> 00:41:23,240
 While the context is different from Liberia,

641
00:41:23,240 --> 00:41:26,880
 similar challenges remain,

642
00:41:26,880 --> 00:41:29,840
 cultural complexity, limited resources,

643
00:41:29,840 --> 00:41:33,200
 and evolving social realities.

644
00:41:33,200 --> 00:41:36,360
 It is important to note here that the Lottery Mission

645
00:41:36,360 --> 00:41:41,320
 never had U.S. missionaries serving in India.

646
00:41:41,320 --> 00:41:45,880
 Leadership was always Indian citizens and residents.

647
00:41:45,880 --> 00:41:48,000
 And I offer the following lessons.

648
00:41:48,000 --> 00:41:51,480
 First, the mission demonstrates the value

649
00:41:51,480 --> 00:41:54,720
 of incarnational leadership.

650
00:41:54,720 --> 00:41:57,040
 Leadership must be present, relational,

651
00:41:57,040 --> 00:41:59,800
 and embedded within the community.

652
00:41:59,800 --> 00:42:02,120
 Rather than operating at a distance,

653
00:42:02,120 --> 00:42:05,160
 missionaries have lived among the people,

654
00:42:05,160 --> 00:42:08,960
 built relationships, and engaged everyday realities,

655
00:42:08,960 --> 00:42:12,080
 in part because they have been citizens of India

656
00:42:12,080 --> 00:42:13,880
 for their entire lives.

657
00:42:13,880 --> 00:42:18,680
 This proximity fostered trust and credibility.

658
00:42:18,680 --> 00:42:21,640
 It also allowed leaders to identify real needs

659
00:42:21,640 --> 00:42:25,040
 and respond in meaningful ways.

660
00:42:25,040 --> 00:42:26,960
 Leadership in this sense

661
00:42:26,960 --> 00:42:30,160
 was not directive but participatory.

662
00:42:30,160 --> 00:42:31,840
 The lesson is clear.

663
00:42:31,840 --> 00:42:36,840
 Lasting influence is built through presence, not authority.

664
00:42:37,080 --> 00:42:41,880
 Another key lesson is the necessity of holistic vision.

665
00:42:41,880 --> 00:42:44,880
 As another context, leaders in India recognized

666
00:42:44,880 --> 00:42:48,320
 that spiritual ministry could not be separated

667
00:42:48,320 --> 00:42:51,120
 from social and educational developments.

668
00:42:51,120 --> 00:42:54,600
 Schools, literacy programs, and community initiatives

669
00:42:54,600 --> 00:42:57,520
 became central to the mission's work.

670
00:42:57,520 --> 00:43:01,480
 This approach acknowledged that transformation

671
00:43:01,480 --> 00:43:04,960
 involves the whole person and the whole community.

672
00:43:06,160 --> 00:43:08,800
 The Indian context also reveals the importance

673
00:43:08,800 --> 00:43:12,840
 of perseverance in slow-growing environments.

674
00:43:12,840 --> 00:43:16,760
 Unlike settings where growth may be rapid or visible,

675
00:43:16,760 --> 00:43:20,320
 the work in India unfolded gradually.

676
00:43:20,320 --> 00:43:22,160
 Cultural and religious barriers

677
00:43:22,160 --> 00:43:25,800
 meant that progress required patience and consistency.

678
00:43:25,800 --> 00:43:27,480
 Leaders had to remain faithful

679
00:43:27,480 --> 00:43:31,120
 even when results were not immediately apparent.

680
00:43:31,120 --> 00:43:34,320
 This teaches an essential leadership truth.

681
00:43:34,320 --> 00:43:39,320
 Not all meaningful work yields quick outcomes.

682
00:43:39,320 --> 00:43:42,560
 Enduring leaders are those who remain committed

683
00:43:42,560 --> 00:43:47,560
 to their mission despite slow progress.

684
00:43:47,560 --> 00:43:52,600
 We have to trust that long-term faithfulness will bear fruit.

685
00:43:52,600 --> 00:43:57,000
 Additionally, the mission underscores the importance

686
00:43:57,000 --> 00:43:59,360
 of indigenous leadership.

687
00:43:59,360 --> 00:44:03,680
 Sustainable impact depended on supporting local leaders

688
00:44:03,680 --> 00:44:05,520
 who could carry the work forward

689
00:44:05,520 --> 00:44:07,960
 within their cultural context.

690
00:44:07,960 --> 00:44:11,080
 This required intentional investment in education,

691
00:44:11,080 --> 00:44:12,760
 mentorship, and empowerment.

692
00:44:12,760 --> 00:44:16,320
 Rather than maintaining external controls,

693
00:44:16,320 --> 00:44:20,160
 effective leaders prioritize partnership

694
00:44:20,160 --> 00:44:21,920
 and local ownership.

695
00:44:21,920 --> 00:44:25,080
 This reflects a broader leadership principle.

696
00:44:25,080 --> 00:44:29,520
 True success is measured not by how indispensable

697
00:44:29,520 --> 00:44:30,920
 a leader becomes.

698
00:44:32,360 --> 00:44:37,360
 True success is about how well they prepare others

699
00:44:37,360 --> 00:44:40,960
 in their context to lead.

700
00:44:40,960 --> 00:44:46,800
 Finally, the Lotkheri experience in India

701
00:44:46,800 --> 00:44:51,720
 emphasizes faith-centered resilience.

702
00:44:51,720 --> 00:44:56,720
 Leaders drew strength from their spiritual convictions,

703
00:44:56,720 --> 00:45:01,480
 which sustained them through difficulties and uncertainty.

704
00:45:01,480 --> 00:45:04,920
 Their work was not merely a professional endeavor.

705
00:45:04,920 --> 00:45:07,000
 Their work was a calling

706
00:45:07,000 --> 00:45:09,920
 that shaped their endurance and perspective.

707
00:45:09,920 --> 00:45:13,480
 This kind of resilience goes beyond determination.

708
00:45:13,480 --> 00:45:16,520
 It is rooted in a faith that gives meaning

709
00:45:16,520 --> 00:45:19,680
 to sacrifice and perseverance.

710
00:45:19,680 --> 00:45:22,880
 Today, in India, several hundred people

711
00:45:22,880 --> 00:45:27,120
 receive free medical care for leprosy and other diseases.

712
00:45:27,120 --> 00:45:29,920
 More than 10,000 children are enrolled

713
00:45:29,920 --> 00:45:32,400
 in four high-capacity schools,

714
00:45:32,400 --> 00:45:34,400
 and about a dozen churches serve

715
00:45:34,400 --> 00:45:38,640
 where people live in or close to poverty and the periphery.

716
00:45:38,640 --> 00:45:42,880
 Leadership lessons from the Lotkheri mission in India

717
00:45:42,880 --> 00:45:46,960
 point to the importance of humility, presence,

718
00:45:46,960 --> 00:45:51,560
 holistic vision, perseverance, empowering others,

719
00:45:51,560 --> 00:45:54,920
 and adaptability and spiritual grounding.

720
00:45:54,920 --> 00:45:59,920
 These principles remind us that leadership,

721
00:45:59,920 --> 00:46:05,480
 especially in complex and cross-cultural contexts,

722
00:46:05,480 --> 00:46:08,840
 is less about immediate results

723
00:46:08,840 --> 00:46:13,160
 and more about faithful, long-term impact.

724
00:46:13,160 --> 00:46:21,960
 My research did include lessons from Nigeria and Guyana,

725
00:46:22,640 --> 00:46:26,280
 but I want to move to talk about now my formula

726
00:46:26,280 --> 00:46:27,800
 for flourishing.

727
00:46:27,800 --> 00:46:32,640
 From my research about global leadership insights

728
00:46:32,640 --> 00:46:37,320
 with 50 years or more in the Lotkheri Mission Society,

729
00:46:37,320 --> 00:46:39,280
 I've discerned lessons for leadership,

730
00:46:39,280 --> 00:46:42,600
 which I refer to as a formula for flourishing.

731
00:46:42,600 --> 00:46:46,680
 Flourishing in this sense is living with fidelity

732
00:46:46,680 --> 00:46:49,400
 to God's calling in your life.

733
00:46:49,400 --> 00:46:52,960
 One piece of advice that I've given to young leaders

734
00:46:52,960 --> 00:46:55,360
 for decades is this.

735
00:46:55,360 --> 00:46:59,560
 Find God's will for your life and stay in it.

736
00:46:59,560 --> 00:47:02,720
 This does not imply that finding

737
00:47:02,720 --> 00:47:05,280
 or discerning God's will is easy,

738
00:47:05,280 --> 00:47:07,040
 but it does point to the reality

739
00:47:07,040 --> 00:47:11,200
 that serving in the ways that God calls you

740
00:47:11,200 --> 00:47:14,200
 is the best way to orient your life and your work.

741
00:47:14,200 --> 00:47:16,920
 Further, this does not suggest

742
00:47:16,920 --> 00:47:20,360
 that what one discerns in 2026

743
00:47:20,360 --> 00:47:23,960
 will be the same in 2030 or 2036.

744
00:47:23,960 --> 00:47:28,440
 It may be that following your vocational path

745
00:47:28,440 --> 00:47:31,840
 leads you to different stops along the way,

746
00:47:31,840 --> 00:47:36,480
 and that this is how your fidelity is made known.

747
00:47:36,480 --> 00:47:38,720
 Others, however, may get to the place

748
00:47:38,720 --> 00:47:41,920
 where they find a place to serve

749
00:47:41,920 --> 00:47:45,080
 and come to know that to be God's will for their lives.

750
00:47:45,080 --> 00:47:47,400
 Wherever you find yourself,

751
00:47:47,400 --> 00:47:49,560
 my hope is that you will come to know

752
00:47:49,560 --> 00:47:53,520
 your faithful responsiveness to the voice of Jesus

753
00:47:53,520 --> 00:47:55,600
 and the inspiration of the Holy Spirit.

754
00:47:55,600 --> 00:47:59,400
 The formula to flourishing follows.

755
00:47:59,400 --> 00:48:03,880
 One's context of leading

756
00:48:03,880 --> 00:48:07,480
 plus one's capabilities for leading

757
00:48:07,480 --> 00:48:11,140
 should yield to one's content for leading.

758
00:48:12,560 --> 00:48:17,560
 Context plus capabilities should yield content.

759
00:48:17,560 --> 00:48:20,760
 One way of thinking about context

760
00:48:20,760 --> 00:48:23,920
 is related to settings, time periods,

761
00:48:23,920 --> 00:48:28,360
 beliefs and traditions, and situational circumstances.

762
00:48:28,360 --> 00:48:30,600
 One can think about capabilities

763
00:48:30,600 --> 00:48:33,040
 as your skill level to perform.

764
00:48:33,040 --> 00:48:35,160
 In other words, where you serve

765
00:48:35,160 --> 00:48:36,960
 and what you are able to do

766
00:48:36,960 --> 00:48:39,040
 should give rise to the content

767
00:48:39,040 --> 00:48:41,240
 of your leadership or ministry.

768
00:48:41,240 --> 00:48:43,860
 And all of these have variables,

769
00:48:43,860 --> 00:48:48,860
 so there is no fixed setting or set of abilities.

770
00:48:48,860 --> 00:48:52,840
 Contexts change in ways that may be better,

771
00:48:52,840 --> 00:48:54,760
 worse, or just different.

772
00:48:54,760 --> 00:48:57,020
 Capabilities change in relationships

773
00:48:57,020 --> 00:48:58,900
 to education and experience.

774
00:48:58,900 --> 00:49:02,400
 And consequently, the formula for flourishing

775
00:49:02,400 --> 00:49:05,560
 is impacted by any number of variables

776
00:49:05,560 --> 00:49:09,660
 that can be in movement at different times.

777
00:49:09,660 --> 00:49:11,360
 The Lycari mission in Liberia

778
00:49:11,360 --> 00:49:15,040
 was led for more than 30 years by Cora and W.H. Thomas.

779
00:49:15,040 --> 00:49:17,880
 He was an educator, she was a pastor,

780
00:49:17,880 --> 00:49:20,120
 I'm sorry, she was an educator,

781
00:49:20,120 --> 00:49:22,680
 and he was a pastor and administrator.

782
00:49:22,680 --> 00:49:25,400
 Liberia was developing as a country,

783
00:49:25,400 --> 00:49:27,420
 so the school that they organized

784
00:49:27,420 --> 00:49:30,240
 focused on academic and vocational training

785
00:49:30,240 --> 00:49:31,840
 in a Christian environment

786
00:49:31,840 --> 00:49:34,640
 in order to help students mature intellectually

787
00:49:34,640 --> 00:49:38,240
 and spiritually and contribute to democracy.

788
00:49:38,240 --> 00:49:41,400
 The focus more than 100 years later

789
00:49:41,400 --> 00:49:44,640
 is very similar with additional contributions

790
00:49:44,640 --> 00:49:47,280
 emphasizing girls' education

791
00:49:47,280 --> 00:49:49,480
 and enrolling Muslim students

792
00:49:49,480 --> 00:49:52,200
 who desire a multi-faith experience,

793
00:49:52,200 --> 00:49:55,180
 providing water, sanitation, and hygiene resources

794
00:49:55,180 --> 00:49:58,300
 for students without that stability,

795
00:49:58,300 --> 00:50:01,800
 and providing meals to help address food insecurity.

796
00:50:01,800 --> 00:50:06,500
 The ongoing mission impact is connected to the context

797
00:50:06,500 --> 00:50:10,440
 and capabilities of the founders and their successors

798
00:50:10,440 --> 00:50:12,920
 with the school as one of the most recognized

799
00:50:12,920 --> 00:50:16,340
 educational institutions in the country.

800
00:50:16,340 --> 00:50:17,920
 The Lycari mission in India

801
00:50:17,920 --> 00:50:20,440
 began with an evangelistic thrust

802
00:50:20,440 --> 00:50:23,680
 because of the leadership of Abner Nelson.

803
00:50:23,680 --> 00:50:25,920
 He was an evangelist.

804
00:50:25,920 --> 00:50:29,720
 And it expanded to maternal leprosy

805
00:50:29,720 --> 00:50:31,480
 and care for the indigent

806
00:50:31,480 --> 00:50:36,160
 once Abner married Ivy Nelson, who was a physician.

807
00:50:36,160 --> 00:50:39,400
 So today, these 10,000 children and youth

808
00:50:39,400 --> 00:50:41,960
 enrolled in schools from Hindu, Muslim,

809
00:50:41,960 --> 00:50:46,000
 and Christian contexts are there

810
00:50:46,000 --> 00:50:49,600
 because of the capability and context

811
00:50:49,600 --> 00:50:52,360
 of the leaders and those who followed.

812
00:50:52,360 --> 00:50:56,920
 These are two examples that demonstrate

813
00:50:56,920 --> 00:51:01,240
 how content is born out of context and capabilities.

814
00:51:01,240 --> 00:51:05,400
 Ministry impact can outlive leaders

815
00:51:05,400 --> 00:51:07,920
 and good leadership seeks to ensure

816
