01:05:01,680 --> 01:05:06,280
 and we build in such a leadership pattern

1090
01:05:06,280 --> 01:05:08,360
 in our pastoral team meeting,

1091
01:05:08,360 --> 01:05:10,480
 in our deacon meeting.

1092
01:05:10,480 --> 01:05:12,480
 And it go down,

1093
01:05:12,480 --> 01:05:15,520
 even go down to our other committee,

1094
01:05:15,520 --> 01:05:17,240
 subcommittee meetings.

1095
01:05:17,240 --> 01:05:18,480
 So that's why in our church,

1096
01:05:18,480 --> 01:05:20,640
 we seldom come across this crash,

1097
01:05:20,640 --> 01:05:22,520
 or all those stuff.

1098
01:05:22,520 --> 01:05:24,360
 So this is one story.

1099
01:05:24,360 --> 01:05:25,440
 And that story,

1100
01:05:25,440 --> 01:05:28,160
 when I serve as a pastor,

1101
01:05:28,160 --> 01:05:30,720
 although I could virtually communicate

1102
01:05:30,720 --> 01:05:33,640
 well with every leaders and members,

1103
01:05:33,640 --> 01:05:35,400
 I noticed something,

1104
01:05:35,400 --> 01:05:38,880
 sometimes something deep down in my heart,

1105
01:05:38,880 --> 01:05:42,400
 I, maybe something too personal,

1106
01:05:42,400 --> 01:05:45,160
 perhaps some of my discontent,

1107
01:05:45,160 --> 01:05:47,120
 or disappointment,

1108
01:05:47,120 --> 01:05:50,800
 or perhaps some of my frustration,

1109
01:05:50,800 --> 01:05:52,000
 or anxiety,

1110
01:05:52,000 --> 01:05:53,080
 or fear,

1111
01:05:53,080 --> 01:05:55,960
 or even temptation,

1112
01:05:55,960 --> 01:05:56,800
 we come to the,

1113
01:05:56,800 --> 01:06:00,640
 I come to the edge of sinning.

1114
01:06:00,640 --> 01:06:05,640
 So, and I thought, hmm, I could not share with our deacons,

1115
01:06:05,640 --> 01:06:07,880
 our pastor, or our church members.

1116
01:06:07,880 --> 01:06:10,320
 But in the end,

1117
01:06:10,320 --> 01:06:13,640
 I lined up a few senior pastor

1118
01:06:13,640 --> 01:06:15,840
 from every corner of the city.

1119
01:06:15,840 --> 01:06:21,160
 So they came from different corner of the city.

1120
01:06:21,160 --> 01:06:23,480
 So we come together regularly.

1121
01:06:23,480 --> 01:06:26,360
 We usually pick our Monday morning,

1122
01:06:26,360 --> 01:06:28,440
 nine o'clock to 12 o'clock,

1123
01:06:28,440 --> 01:06:30,400
 we have three hours sharing.

1124
01:06:30,400 --> 01:06:32,320
 We share ourselves,

1125
01:06:32,320 --> 01:06:34,160
 what they come across,

1126
01:06:34,160 --> 01:06:35,880
 our family,

1127
01:06:35,880 --> 01:06:38,080
 did we fight with our wives,

1128
01:06:38,080 --> 01:06:42,440
 our frustration in the church ministry,

1129
01:06:42,440 --> 01:06:44,280
 our anxiety,

1130
01:06:44,280 --> 01:06:45,560
 all those stuff.

1131
01:06:45,560 --> 01:06:50,560
 We meet once a quarter.

1132
01:06:50,560 --> 01:06:53,160
 So around four times a year.

1133
01:06:53,160 --> 01:06:54,920
 So then we have,

1134
01:06:54,920 --> 01:06:57,520
 after three hours sharing,

1135
01:06:57,520 --> 01:07:00,960
 we pray for one another.

1136
01:07:00,960 --> 01:07:05,760
 And that group lasts for 20 years.

1137
01:07:05,760 --> 01:07:10,560
 We develop a strong friendship.

1138
01:07:10,560 --> 01:07:14,680
 And we develop that we can become our brother's watcher.

1139
01:07:14,680 --> 01:07:17,360
 We watch out for our brothers.

1140
01:07:17,360 --> 01:07:22,360
 And that help us to sort of avoid certain moral failure,

1141
01:07:27,200 --> 01:07:32,200
 or we can honestly spit out,

1142
01:07:32,200 --> 01:07:36,400
 say, "Hey, brothers, you should not doing that.

1143
01:07:36,400 --> 01:07:38,160
 Hey, brother, you should not doing this."

1144
01:07:38,160 --> 01:07:39,760
 So on and so forth.

1145
01:07:39,760 --> 01:07:44,760
 So, and I think that's friendship.

1146
01:07:44,760 --> 01:07:49,000
 Help me to be more sustainable

1147
01:07:49,000 --> 01:07:54,000
 that I could thrive in my ministry.

1148
01:07:55,440 --> 01:08:00,400
 Now, the purpose of what I tell you all these two stories

1149
01:08:00,400 --> 01:08:03,080
 is point to one common goal

1150
01:08:03,080 --> 01:08:05,200
 is that for a leader to be flourishing

1151
01:08:05,200 --> 01:08:06,520
 or thriving in ministry,

1152
01:08:06,520 --> 01:08:10,760
 we need to form a hub,

1153
01:08:10,760 --> 01:08:12,320
 a learning hub,

1154
01:08:12,320 --> 01:08:13,720
 a learning group,

1155
01:08:13,720 --> 01:08:15,720
 a learning organization

1156
01:08:15,720 --> 01:08:19,240
 that we can provide a test tool

1157
01:08:19,240 --> 01:08:20,600
 that we can,

1158
01:08:20,600 --> 01:08:25,080
 for people to learn how to lead.

1159
01:08:25,080 --> 01:08:30,080
 So what I mean is to become a thriving leadership,

1160
01:08:30,080 --> 01:08:36,080
 it never should be an individual one.

1161
01:08:36,080 --> 01:08:37,720
 It should be a collective one.

1162
01:08:37,720 --> 01:08:39,320
 It should be a team one.

1163
01:08:39,320 --> 01:08:41,040
 It should be a collaborative one.

1164
01:08:41,040 --> 01:08:47,000
 So hopefully that would respond nicely

1165
01:08:47,000 --> 01:08:49,040
 to what you share with us.

1166
01:08:49,040 --> 01:08:50,600
 Okay, so thank you very much.

1167
01:08:50,600 --> 01:08:54,760
 (audience applauding)

1168
01:08:56,080 --> 01:09:00,280
 - Thank you very much, Dr. Goldlee,

1169
01:09:00,280 --> 01:09:03,360
 for widening our perspective.

1170
01:09:03,360 --> 01:09:06,880
 So taking our focus not just on ourselves,

1171
01:09:06,880 --> 01:09:08,520
 but what God is doing,

1172
01:09:08,520 --> 01:09:10,000
 what the whole world is doing,

1173
01:09:10,000 --> 01:09:12,440
 and also not just the present moment,

1174
01:09:12,440 --> 01:09:13,880
 but the past and the future.

1175
01:09:13,880 --> 01:09:17,000
 And thank you very much for Reverend Michael

1176
01:09:17,000 --> 01:09:20,640
 that you complete the whole world by adding in Australia.

1177
01:09:20,640 --> 01:09:23,240
 Very insightful.

1178
01:09:23,240 --> 01:09:27,200
 So I first, before the Q&A time,

1179
01:09:27,200 --> 01:09:28,880
 like to ask if Dr. Goldlee,

1180
01:09:28,880 --> 01:09:33,080
 you have something to respond to his response or?

1181
01:09:33,080 --> 01:09:39,600
 - Thank you so much for adding the story.

1182
01:09:39,600 --> 01:09:47,520
 One of the things that I was deliberately decided to do

1183
01:09:47,520 --> 01:09:51,200
 is the references that I was making

1184
01:09:51,200 --> 01:09:56,200
 were definitively non-Western.

1185
01:09:56,200 --> 01:10:05,080
 And so often Australia is considered Western

1186
01:10:05,080 --> 01:10:11,560
 even though it's not in the North Atlantic West.

1187
01:10:11,560 --> 01:10:12,720
 - And South, just kidding.

1188
01:10:12,720 --> 01:10:14,400
 - Yeah, and South.

1189
01:10:14,400 --> 01:10:18,400
 And so, but I do appreciate you're talking about

1190
01:10:18,400 --> 01:10:22,280
 the importance of community.

1191
01:10:22,280 --> 01:10:26,960
 And because we, part of leadership,

1192
01:10:26,960 --> 01:10:32,480
 leadership can be isolating.

1193
01:10:32,480 --> 01:10:38,440
 And if we don't intentionally work on building communities,

1194
01:10:38,440 --> 01:10:43,880
 we can self-isolate.

1195
01:10:45,880 --> 01:10:50,880
 I'm not sure I agree with the way

1196
01:10:50,880 --> 01:10:55,200
 that some people talk about leadership is lonely.

1197
01:10:55,200 --> 01:10:58,680
 And I do understand what they're saying,

1198
01:10:58,680 --> 01:11:02,960
 but it gets lonely if we don't create the partnerships.

1199
01:11:02,960 --> 01:11:07,760
 So it's not like it's doing something to us,

1200
01:11:07,760 --> 01:11:10,280
 it's how we inhabit.

1201
01:11:10,280 --> 01:11:13,440
 And so if we don't build relationships,

1202
01:11:13,440 --> 01:11:14,800
 then we will become lonely.

1203
01:11:14,800 --> 01:11:17,960
 So I just really appreciate that

1204
01:11:17,960 --> 01:11:21,680
 because that makes us vulnerable,

1205
01:11:21,680 --> 01:11:23,640
 more vulnerable to sin

1206
01:11:23,640 --> 01:11:28,680
 when we are not in communities of support

1207
01:11:28,680 --> 01:11:32,160
 and mutuality and accountability.

1208
01:11:32,160 --> 01:11:35,360
 So thank you for naming how important that is.

1209
01:11:35,360 --> 01:11:36,200
 - Thank you.

1210
01:11:36,200 --> 01:11:38,480
 So it is now question and answer time.

1211
01:11:38,480 --> 01:11:41,560
 We have a microphone in the center.

1212
01:11:41,560 --> 01:11:43,840
 If you have comments, questions,

1213
01:11:43,840 --> 01:11:47,840
 you're welcome to come to the mic and ask.

1214
01:11:47,840 --> 01:11:48,880
 Say your name first.

1215
01:11:48,880 --> 01:11:54,880
 And also, if you don't feel comfortable speaking English,

1216
01:11:54,880 --> 01:11:58,680
 you can ask in Chinese and I'll try to translate.

1217
01:11:58,680 --> 01:12:00,200
 That's also okay.

1218
01:12:00,200 --> 01:12:03,200
 So the time is yours.

1219
01:12:03,200 --> 01:12:06,160
 If anybody would like to ask any questions.

1220
01:12:14,840 --> 01:12:17,320
 - Hello, my name is Kin Lui.

1221
01:12:17,320 --> 01:12:22,320
 I teach theology and church history here in CUSD.

1222
01:12:22,320 --> 01:12:26,840
 So first, as a church history, as a church historian,

1223
01:12:26,840 --> 01:12:31,200
 I'm grateful you mentioned the importance of heritage.

1224
01:12:31,200 --> 01:12:33,760
 You even sing the song, "The Old Rocket Course,"

1225
01:12:33,760 --> 01:12:36,360
 which I can more or less remember the lyrics,

1226
01:12:36,360 --> 01:12:37,800
 at least the first verse,

1227
01:12:37,800 --> 01:12:40,200
 that I seldom heard it sung in the church

1228
01:12:40,200 --> 01:12:41,880
 in Hong Kong right now.

1229
01:12:41,880 --> 01:12:46,640
 But I always like to ask some provocative questions.

1230
01:12:46,640 --> 01:12:49,000
 So I'll just be provocative.

1231
01:12:49,000 --> 01:12:50,360
 I'll ask you this, okay?

1232
01:12:50,360 --> 01:12:56,800
 You mentioned that a leader should recognize

1233
01:12:56,800 --> 01:13:01,760
 that he's receiver of a great tradition.

1234
01:13:01,760 --> 01:13:04,800
 He should not be too eager to renovate

1235
01:13:04,800 --> 01:13:09,720
 and he should not be too eager to look at the figures,

1236
01:13:09,720 --> 01:13:11,120
 the short-term result.

1237
01:13:11,120 --> 01:13:14,520
 But of course, fuller seminary is also the birthplace

1238
01:13:14,520 --> 01:13:16,960
 of the church growth movement,

1239
01:13:16,960 --> 01:13:21,200
 which measured the effectiveness of church ministry

1240
01:13:21,200 --> 01:13:24,240
 in terms of some ratio, this ratio, that ratio.

1241
01:13:24,240 --> 01:13:25,800
 I'm not gonna explain church growth here,

1242
01:13:25,800 --> 01:13:28,880
 but it's KPI in a way, okay?

1243
01:13:28,880 --> 01:13:30,960
 So my question really is this.

1244
01:13:30,960 --> 01:13:35,040
 So how do I distinguish,

1245
01:13:35,040 --> 01:13:37,200
 suppose I do a certain kind of ministry

1246
01:13:37,200 --> 01:13:40,240
 and the result is coming in, is not coming in.

1247
01:13:40,240 --> 01:13:45,080
 How do I distinguish that whether I'm just being stubborn?

1248
01:13:45,080 --> 01:13:46,320
 I shouldn't do this.

1249
01:13:46,320 --> 01:13:48,600
 It's failure, but I just keep doing it

1250
01:13:48,600 --> 01:13:51,040
 because somehow I have this fantasy

1251
01:13:51,040 --> 01:13:54,200
 that this is God's task for me.

1252
01:13:54,200 --> 01:13:58,000
 How do I distinguish this from the other side is,

1253
01:13:58,000 --> 01:14:00,240
 well, we should not look at the short-term result,

1254
01:14:00,240 --> 01:14:02,680
 it's the legacy, it's the long-term result

1255
01:14:02,680 --> 01:14:03,560
 that I'm looking at.

1256
01:14:03,560 --> 01:14:06,600
 How do I distinguish between the two?

1257
01:14:06,600 --> 01:14:08,400
 Please give me some wisdom.

1258
01:14:10,240 --> 01:14:15,240
 - Thank you for the question

1259
01:14:15,240 --> 01:14:18,440
 and thank you for being a theologian

1260
01:14:18,440 --> 01:14:22,440
 and being provocative.

1261
01:14:22,440 --> 01:14:28,400
 I think among the things to consider is that

1262
01:14:28,400 --> 01:14:37,240
 leaders, I think it's very rare

1263
01:14:39,040 --> 01:14:44,040
 that leaders should be trying to serve

1264
01:14:44,040 --> 01:14:51,320
 without conversation partners

1265
01:14:51,320 --> 01:14:57,480
 who can help them interrogate their assumptions.

1266
01:14:57,480 --> 01:15:05,360
 You know, I think about the parable Jesus tells

1267
01:15:05,400 --> 01:15:10,400
 about the landowner at a large crop

1268
01:15:10,400 --> 01:15:16,880
 and decided he talks to himself.

1269
01:15:16,880 --> 01:15:20,440
 He says, what I will do is I will turn down my barns

1270
01:15:20,440 --> 01:15:23,640
 and I'll build bigger barns and I'll say to myself,

1271
01:15:23,640 --> 01:15:26,920
 well, he's having a conversation with himself,

1272
01:15:26,920 --> 01:15:31,560
 which is not the most fruitful conversation for us to have

1273
01:15:31,560 --> 01:15:33,640
 when we just talk to ourselves.

1274
01:15:33,640 --> 01:15:37,400
 And so I think one of the things to help leaders

1275
01:15:37,400 --> 01:15:43,400
 is to have some wise conversation partners

1276
01:15:43,400 --> 01:15:50,160
 to help them check their own assumptions

1277
01:15:50,160 --> 01:15:53,600
 and call them into accountability

1278
01:15:53,600 --> 01:15:58,040
 and we need to be able to give permission to some people

1279
01:15:58,040 --> 01:16:01,200
 to be very direct with us.

1280
01:16:02,040 --> 01:16:07,040
 And I have very, very few colleagues

1281
01:16:07,040 --> 01:16:14,360
 who if they know that if they tell me to stop,

1282
01:16:14,360 --> 01:16:18,840
 I'm going to stop even if I want to go

1283
01:16:18,840 --> 01:16:24,040
 because I can't trust my own ego

1284
01:16:24,040 --> 01:16:28,960
 because of my anthropology.

1285
01:16:30,480 --> 01:16:34,040
 If I don't have other accountability partners,

1286
01:16:34,040 --> 01:16:37,080
 I don't take sin seriously enough.

1287
01:16:37,080 --> 01:16:39,640
 So I think one of the things that we need to do

1288
01:16:39,640 --> 01:16:44,640
 is have some wisdom close by that we give permission

1289
01:16:44,640 --> 01:16:48,200
 to stop us in our tracks.

1290
01:16:48,200 --> 01:16:52,480
 I also think that it's important for us

1291
01:16:52,480 --> 01:16:57,200
 to not try to be clever all the time

1292
01:16:58,960 --> 01:17:03,440
 and it's a temptation to try to come up

1293
01:17:03,440 --> 01:17:08,440
 with some new angle or some new expression.

1294
01:17:08,440 --> 01:17:13,200
 And we do need to be fresh

1295
01:17:13,200 --> 01:17:18,200
 and we do need to not have a stale pond

1296
01:17:18,200 --> 01:17:23,200
 but have fresh tributaries coming in.

1297
01:17:23,200 --> 01:17:26,600
 But I think there's also a temptation

1298
01:17:27,840 --> 01:17:31,480
 to try to be clever and innovative.

1299
01:17:31,480 --> 01:17:33,160
 There's not that much.

1300
01:17:33,160 --> 01:17:38,600
 One has said that there's nothing new under the sun.

1301
01:17:38,600 --> 01:17:44,480
 And sometimes the most innovative thing

1302
01:17:44,480 --> 01:17:46,400
 that we can do as Christians

1303
01:17:46,400 --> 01:17:52,520
 is to go back to what gave the early church its magic.

1304
01:17:54,680 --> 01:17:58,760
 I made a brief reference earlier to Kevin Rowe's

1305
01:17:58,760 --> 01:18:03,400
 Christianity's Surprise, who talks about three things.

1306
01:18:03,400 --> 01:18:06,160
 One is the story of everything.

1307
01:18:06,160 --> 01:18:13,120
 Our story is aligned with what God's story,

1308
01:18:13,120 --> 01:18:14,680
 that's the story of everything.

1309
01:18:14,680 --> 01:18:19,240
 And the surprise of humanity

1310
01:18:19,240 --> 01:18:23,920
 that in the Roman Empire there was no concept

1311
01:18:23,920 --> 01:18:28,920
 of humanity that is born in the identity of Christ.

1312
01:18:28,920 --> 01:18:38,560
 And then the institutions that are born

1313
01:18:38,560 --> 01:18:42,120
 out of that imago Dei.

1314
01:18:42,120 --> 01:18:49,080
 One of the things that might make sense for us to do

1315
01:18:49,080 --> 01:18:52,800
 is go back to the early church,

1316
01:18:52,800 --> 01:18:57,800
 not to try to replicate it but to be inspired by it.

1317
01:18:57,800 --> 01:19:05,680
 I'm enjoying the AI exercise,

1318
01:19:05,680 --> 01:19:07,800
 and I'm curious in the United States,

1319
01:19:07,800 --> 01:19:09,720
 I'm from the Southern United States,

1320
01:19:09,720 --> 01:19:12,520
 so I have a Southern accent,

1321
01:19:12,520 --> 01:19:17,520
 and I don't know how the AI was trained.

1322
01:19:17,520 --> 01:19:22,280
 And so it's quite, okay, all right.

1323
01:19:23,800 --> 01:19:28,800
 But we're having conversations in the United States,

1324
01:19:28,800 --> 01:19:32,800
 a number of theological communities

1325
01:19:32,800 --> 01:19:37,800
 about what are the implications for humanity with AI?

1326
01:19:37,800 --> 01:19:45,360
 And I'm wondering, how about we go back,

1327
01:19:49,120 --> 01:19:53,520
 AI cannot redefine humanity for believers.

1328
01:19:53,520 --> 01:19:57,800
 We are created in the image of God.

1329
01:19:57,800 --> 01:20:03,280
 And God was in Christ reconciling the world to God's self.

1330
01:20:03,280 --> 01:20:07,680
 And Jesus is the new Adam.

1331
01:20:07,680 --> 01:20:12,840
 And in him we have life and we have it abundantly.

1332
01:20:12,840 --> 01:20:16,680
 There's nothing AI can do to that.

1333
01:20:18,320 --> 01:20:20,920
 So I think that we need to introduce that

1334
01:20:20,920 --> 01:20:23,760
 into the conversations.

1335
01:20:23,760 --> 01:20:32,520
 - Maybe my quick answer to your question

1336
01:20:32,520 --> 01:20:35,880
 is that I think KPI,

1337
01:20:35,880 --> 01:20:40,680
 more or less the contemporary people mentioned that,

1338
01:20:40,680 --> 01:20:45,680
 but I just wonder how God's KPI is.

1339
01:20:48,120 --> 01:20:51,840
 I would say to be a thriving leader

1340
01:20:51,840 --> 01:20:55,080
 is more about his faithfulness,

1341
01:20:55,080 --> 01:21:00,080
 more about he's faithful to God assigned to the assignment,

1342
01:21:00,080 --> 01:21:04,400
 assigned to the ministry, scope, or whatever.

1343
01:21:04,400 --> 01:21:08,960
 Whether the person bear fruit

1344
01:21:08,960 --> 01:21:13,960
 or produce any big harvest, whatever,

1345
01:21:13,960 --> 01:21:16,800
 we are not responsible for that.

1346
01:21:16,800 --> 01:21:18,600
 It's God responsible for that.

1347
01:21:18,600 --> 01:21:21,680
 So that's why I would say,

1348
01:21:21,680 --> 01:21:26,680
 although FULA is the ground of church growth,

1349
01:21:26,680 --> 01:21:29,600
 so just now in the dinner,

1350
01:21:29,600 --> 01:21:32,240
 we mentioned about that Donald McGovern,

1351
01:21:32,240 --> 01:21:35,040
 so the homogeneous unit principle.

1352
01:21:35,040 --> 01:21:43,600
 Nowadays, we all forget about this theory now.

1353
01:21:43,600 --> 01:21:45,880
 Sorry about that, sorry.

1354
01:21:47,800 --> 01:21:50,880
 - Yeah, well, I thought, yeah,

1355
01:21:50,880 --> 01:21:52,760
 thank you for mentioning church growth

1356
01:21:52,760 --> 01:21:57,760
 because that has come under some critique

1357
01:21:57,760 --> 01:22:05,640
 in the United States context.

1358
01:22:05,640 --> 01:22:08,720
 Now, if my recollection is right,

1359
01:22:08,720 --> 01:22:13,720
 some of that grounding theory came out

1360
01:22:17,480 --> 01:22:21,240
 of certain international contexts

1361
01:22:21,240 --> 01:22:24,920
 where you had, I think in India,

1362
01:22:24,920 --> 01:22:29,680
 where you had certain rigid experiences

1363
01:22:29,680 --> 01:22:36,600
 in contexts that did not allow for fluid movement

1364
01:22:36,600 --> 01:22:38,320
 like you do in the United States.

1365
01:22:38,320 --> 01:22:41,440
 So one of the things that happened in the US

1366
01:22:41,440 --> 01:22:45,840
 is you had these, using this homogeneous principle

1367
01:22:45,840 --> 01:22:49,920
 has contributed to the fragmentation of the church.

1368
01:22:49,920 --> 01:22:56,800
 And so that is under review and probably like a lot of things.

1369
01:22:56,800 --> 01:23:06,760
 On one hand, there are positive contributions.

1370
01:23:06,760 --> 01:23:10,640
 On the other hand, there are negative consequences

1371
01:23:10,640 --> 01:23:14,360
 and we have to figure out how to modulate

1372
01:23:14,360 --> 01:23:19,360
 and live in it, but everything needs to be subjected

1373
01:23:19,360 --> 01:23:26,800
 to honest critique and refinement.

1374
01:23:26,800 --> 01:23:28,120
 Thank you for naming that.

1375
01:23:28,120 --> 01:23:33,200
 - Other questions?

1376
01:23:33,200 --> 01:23:36,680
 Actually, I have a follow-up question

1377
01:23:36,680 --> 01:23:39,080
 for, I guess, both of you.

1378
01:23:39,080 --> 01:23:41,120
 I think it is important that you mentioned

1379
01:23:41,120 --> 01:23:44,720
 faithfulness, steadfastness, look at long-term,

1380
01:23:44,720 --> 01:23:45,560
 things like that.

1381
01:23:45,560 --> 01:23:47,520
 It is very important.

1382
01:23:47,520 --> 01:23:49,440
 But I guess my question is a little bit follow-up

1383
01:23:49,440 --> 01:23:51,120
 with what Kim just said.

1384
01:23:51,120 --> 01:23:55,200
 What if the person is just stubbornness, right?

1385
01:23:55,200 --> 01:23:57,200
 So my question is that, or actually, Michael,

1386
01:23:57,200 --> 01:24:00,560
 you mentioned in your response that today's problem

1387
01:24:00,560 --> 01:24:05,560
 is come out of the success of yesterday's success, right?

1388
01:24:05,560 --> 01:24:07,760
 Something like that.

1389
01:24:07,760 --> 01:24:10,880
 So my question is, how to tell today

1390
01:24:10,880 --> 01:24:15,200
 that a ministry once flourishing is actually

1391
01:24:15,200 --> 01:24:17,600
 not doing well and should stop?

1392
01:24:17,600 --> 01:24:19,120
 You see what I'm saying?

1393
01:24:19,120 --> 01:24:24,120
 'Cause in Hong Kong, things are changing so quickly.

1394
01:24:24,120 --> 01:24:30,040
 But we still feel that there are some ways

1395
01:24:30,040 --> 01:24:33,240
 of doing ministry that it's actually kind of outdated,

1396
01:24:33,240 --> 01:24:37,440
 but a lot of people still want to stick with it.

1397
01:24:37,440 --> 01:24:42,440
 But it is kind of difficult to tell, but how to tell

1398
01:24:42,440 --> 01:24:49,520
 if a ministry should stop now instead of still faithful to it?

1399
01:24:49,520 --> 01:24:52,400
 So that's my question, yeah.

1400
01:24:52,400 --> 01:24:55,440
 - You go first.

1401
01:24:55,440 --> 01:24:56,280
 - Okay.

1402
01:24:56,280 --> 01:25:04,600
 I think one of the main point I would watch out is that

1403
01:25:07,440 --> 01:25:12,440
 I always have to read the people's need, the culture.

1404
01:25:12,440 --> 01:25:20,440
 For example, nowadays, say for example, 30 years ago,

1405
01:25:20,440 --> 01:25:25,200
 in Hong Kong, we have a lot of this evangelism rally,

1406
01:25:25,200 --> 01:25:27,120
 (speaks in foreign language)

1407
01:25:27,120 --> 01:25:32,120
 and the Hong Kong stadium to 20,000 people,

1408
01:25:32,120 --> 01:25:35,760
 et cetera, et cetera.

1409
01:25:35,760 --> 01:25:38,880
 So in those days, it was very flourishing, I think,

1410
01:25:38,880 --> 01:25:43,880
 that the result is quite a lot, actually.

1411
01:25:43,880 --> 01:25:48,640
 But nowadays, I just wonder how many people

1412
01:25:48,640 --> 01:25:53,160
 were still that keen for those kind of rally?

1413
01:25:53,160 --> 01:25:54,320
 How would I know?

1414
01:25:54,320 --> 01:25:59,320
 I never become a pilgrim and speak in the Hong Kong stadium.

1415
01:25:59,320 --> 01:26:02,120
 But what I mean, I have to talk to people,

1416
01:26:02,120 --> 01:26:07,120
 hey, why don't you attend this kind of evangelism rally?

1417
01:26:07,120 --> 01:26:12,000
 Even our local church, we also organize

1418
01:26:12,000 --> 01:26:14,640
 those evangelism meeting, (speaks in foreign language)

1419
01:26:14,640 --> 01:26:17,520
 and not many come.

1420
01:26:17,520 --> 01:26:20,480
 Even our Christian members, they don't invite

1421
01:26:20,480 --> 01:26:23,640
 their non-Christian neighbors or their non-Christian

1422
01:26:23,640 --> 01:26:28,320
 relatives come over to attend those meetings.

1423
01:26:28,320 --> 01:26:32,600
 I always ask why, because many of them,

1424
01:26:32,600 --> 01:26:35,280
 they say, I don't want this one way,

1425
01:26:35,280 --> 01:26:38,200
 where a person talk to us.

1426
01:26:38,200 --> 01:26:39,920
 We want more communication.

1427
01:26:39,920 --> 01:26:41,200
 We want more dialogue.

1428
01:26:41,200 --> 01:26:43,680
 I want to have question and answer.

1429
01:26:43,680 --> 01:26:46,360
 Nowadays, this is their culture.

1430
01:26:46,360 --> 01:26:48,360
 So in that case, we can't stick to,

1431
01:26:48,360 --> 01:26:53,360
 okay, 30 years ago, we have good result.

1432
01:26:53,360 --> 01:26:58,080
 Why don't we persist that?

1433
01:26:58,080 --> 01:27:00,800
 So that's why, one trick is that we have to read

1434
01:27:00,800 --> 01:27:03,360
 the culture, we have to understand people's,

1435
01:27:03,360 --> 01:27:06,840
 what is the best way to do ministry?

1436
01:27:06,840 --> 01:27:08,640
 So this is my simple answer.

1437
01:27:08,640 --> 01:27:13,400
 - Thank you for that question.

1438
01:27:13,400 --> 01:27:18,040
 I think sometimes we have to inquire

1439
01:27:18,040 --> 01:27:21,920
 of what is the purpose we're trying to achieve.

1440
01:27:21,920 --> 01:27:27,560
 If somebody wants to have a rally,

1441
01:27:27,560 --> 01:27:29,160
 what's the purpose of the rally?

1442
01:27:29,160 --> 01:27:35,280
 And is the rally the best way to achieve what the goal is?

1443
01:27:35,280 --> 01:27:41,400
 I think also, when I was talking about this formula

1444
01:27:41,400 --> 01:27:48,080
 for flourishing, contexts change.

1445
01:27:48,080 --> 01:27:53,480
 So one of the reasons these big crusades and rallies

1446
01:27:56,280 --> 01:28:00,480
 were so popular is one, they were innovative.

1447
01:28:00,480 --> 01:28:05,840
 But it's not innovative anymore.

1448
01:28:05,840 --> 01:28:11,840
 Also, they weren't competing with the same things

1449
01:28:11,840 --> 01:28:13,040
 that they are now.

1450
01:28:13,040 --> 01:28:18,560
 Now, I don't, let me give you an example

1451
01:28:18,560 --> 01:28:19,840
 of in the United States.

1452
01:28:19,840 --> 01:28:22,360
 I don't know how it plays out in Hong Kong.

1453
01:28:23,240 --> 01:28:28,240
 In the United States, a generation or so ago,

1454
01:28:28,240 --> 01:28:35,200
 you did not have Sunday sports leagues,

1455
01:28:35,200 --> 01:28:39,760
 like soccer and basketball.

1456
01:28:39,760 --> 01:28:44,520
 And so on Sunday mornings now in the United States,

1457
01:28:44,520 --> 01:28:49,840
 you have all these sports activities and opportunities

1458
01:28:49,840 --> 01:28:54,840
 that are going on that were not going on at another time.

1459
01:28:54,840 --> 01:28:58,080
 So does that mean that people's commitments

1460
01:28:58,080 --> 01:28:59,880
 to the church has changed?

1461
01:28:59,880 --> 01:29:03,800
 Or does it mean that there are more choices

1462
01:29:03,800 --> 01:29:05,000
 that people are making?

1463
01:29:05,000 --> 01:29:07,840
 It's not even the same comparison.

1464
01:29:07,840 --> 01:29:09,920
 That's in the United States.

1465
01:29:09,920 --> 01:29:14,920
 And now, if you have teenagers who are athletes

1466
01:29:16,440 --> 01:29:20,640
 and on travel teams, so they travel on weekends,

1467
01:29:20,640 --> 01:29:25,640
 where there was not that much going on a generation ago,

1468
01:29:25,640 --> 01:29:29,240
 and so the church provided a different kind

1469
01:29:29,240 --> 01:29:33,720
 of socialization experience,

1470
01:29:33,720 --> 01:29:36,320
 that now that happens in other places.

1471
01:29:36,320 --> 01:29:38,880
 So is that a judgment on the church?

1472
01:29:38,880 --> 01:29:45,280
 Or is it saying that the context has changed,

1473
01:29:45,280 --> 01:29:48,240
 so we need to do, your word was adaptive,

1474
01:29:48,240 --> 01:29:55,680
 referring to Heifetz, do we have to do some adaptation

1475
01:29:55,680 --> 01:29:59,320
 because the context has changed?

1476
01:29:59,320 --> 01:30:02,560
 I do think that we do, though,

1477
01:30:02,560 --> 01:30:07,560
 that leaders need to function in communities,

1478
01:30:07,560 --> 01:30:12,200
 and then communities need to discern,

1479
01:30:13,040 --> 01:30:18,040
 help leaders to discern if it's time to do something else.

1480
01:30:18,040 --> 01:30:25,200
 And so leaders should not be given the permission

1481
01:30:25,200 --> 01:30:27,280
 to just make the decision on their own

1482
01:30:27,280 --> 01:30:34,000
 because most of us don't have enough critical self-awareness

1483
01:30:34,000 --> 01:30:39,400
 to evaluate our own effectiveness well.

1484
01:30:42,320 --> 01:30:44,040
 We'll either be too hard on ourselves

1485
01:30:44,040 --> 01:30:46,760
 or too easy on ourselves or something like that.

1486
01:30:46,760 --> 01:30:49,320
 And so I think that communities

1487
01:30:49,320 --> 01:30:51,720
 have to take responsibility.

1488
01:30:51,720 --> 01:30:56,720
 So you think about in Acts, when there was a conflict

1489
01:30:56,720 --> 01:31:01,480
 between the Hellenistic and Grecian widows.

1490
01:31:01,480 --> 01:31:07,360
 So it was the community who said,

1491
01:31:07,360 --> 01:31:10,320
 "We've got a problem, leaders."

1492
01:31:11,480 --> 01:31:16,040
 And the leaders then didn't try to stop ministering in word,

1493
01:31:16,040 --> 01:31:19,720
 but they came up with a solution about delegation,

1494
01:31:19,720 --> 01:31:24,840
 and then it helped to move forward.

1495
01:31:24,840 --> 01:31:29,120
 So the community has to exercise its agency, too,

1496
01:31:29,120 --> 01:31:31,800
 to call for accountability.

1497
01:31:31,800 --> 01:31:36,280
 - Thank you.

1498
01:31:36,280 --> 01:31:37,240
 Any questions?

1499
01:31:37,240 --> 01:31:41,000
 Please, go ahead.

1500
01:31:42,040 --> 01:31:42,880
 - Thank you.

1501
01:31:42,880 --> 01:31:45,560
 We feel better when somebody asks questions.

1502
01:31:45,560 --> 01:31:47,080
 Kind of lonely up here.

1503
01:31:47,080 --> 01:31:48,560
 - Thank you, Dr. David.

1504
01:31:48,560 --> 01:31:52,320
 So you noted that only 11% of Christians

1505
01:31:52,320 --> 01:31:55,520
 lives in the global north and warned that,

1506
01:31:55,520 --> 01:31:56,360
 louder?

1507
01:31:56,360 --> 01:31:57,200
 Okay, sorry.

1508
01:31:57,200 --> 01:31:59,920
 You noted that only 11% of Christians

1509
01:31:59,920 --> 01:32:04,520
 live in the global north and warned all of us

1510
01:32:04,520 --> 01:32:06,640
 of the danger of a single story.

1511
01:32:06,640 --> 01:32:09,240
 So given Hong Kong's history of moving

1512
01:32:09,240 --> 01:32:12,160
 from colonial missions to a local stand,

1513
01:32:12,160 --> 01:32:15,200
 how must Western organization change

1514
01:32:15,200 --> 01:32:20,200
 to stop giving orders and embrace true reciprocity?

1515
01:32:20,200 --> 01:32:22,920
 How can global south leaders protect

1516
01:32:22,920 --> 01:32:24,560
 their own local legacies

1517
01:32:24,560 --> 01:32:27,400
 rather than just follow foreign models?

1518
01:32:27,400 --> 01:32:28,240
 Thank you.

1519
01:32:28,240 --> 01:32:31,080
 - Thank you for the question.

1520
01:32:31,080 --> 01:32:33,800
 If I understand it,

1521
01:32:39,440 --> 01:32:44,440
 a part of what the dynamic is going to need to be

1522
01:32:44,440 --> 01:32:52,920
 is people who have been...

1523
01:32:52,920 --> 01:32:59,960
 I'm trying to get the right word.

1524
01:32:59,960 --> 01:33:02,880
 I'm trying to get the right English word.

1525
01:33:04,520 --> 01:33:09,520
 People who have been imposing their will on others

1526
01:33:09,520 --> 01:33:14,800
 are going to have to grow up

1527
01:33:14,800 --> 01:33:21,200
 and understand the value of mutuality,

1528
01:33:21,200 --> 01:33:27,360
 of shared responsibility and be better listeners.

1529
01:33:27,360 --> 01:33:33,720
 And people who have been subject to the imposition

1530
01:33:34,960 --> 01:33:39,920
 is a challenge to voice their concerns

1531
01:33:39,920 --> 01:33:44,760
 in ways that are being clear about,

1532
01:33:44,760 --> 01:33:49,400
 this is where things have been either painful or harmful

1533
01:33:49,400 --> 01:33:51,560
 or they served another era.

1534
01:33:51,560 --> 01:33:58,240
 So the part of the challenge

1535
01:33:58,240 --> 01:34:03,240
 is to recognize the dignity in all people

1536
01:34:04,960 --> 01:34:09,960
 and for people who have been in the privileged,

1537
01:34:09,960 --> 01:34:18,040
 usually Western context that have more financial

1538
01:34:18,040 --> 01:34:23,040
 and institutional heft really need to be called

1539
01:34:23,040 --> 01:34:28,320
 to repentance about the imposition

1540
01:34:31,040 --> 01:34:36,040
 because too often I think we have allowed

1541
01:34:36,040 --> 01:34:45,240
 non-Christian approaches to inform

1542
01:34:45,240 --> 01:34:50,600
 how we engage with Christian sisters and brothers.

1543
01:34:50,600 --> 01:34:56,080
 A part of the way that shows up in the United States

1544
01:34:56,080 --> 01:34:59,040
 is sometimes if people have more money

1545
01:35:01,200 --> 01:35:06,200
 than they use it in ways that manipulate the process,

1546
01:35:06,200 --> 01:35:14,160
 show that finances are assumed to be privileged.

1547
01:35:14,160 --> 01:35:23,760
 But, and so those who have been socialized with that

1548
01:35:23,760 --> 01:35:27,240
 are gonna need to be called to repentance

1549
01:35:27,240 --> 01:35:31,240
 where it's not about imposing your will

1550
01:35:31,240 --> 01:35:36,240
 but it's about being companions together on the journey

1551
01:35:36,240 --> 01:35:40,600
 and all of us have something else to share.

1552
01:35:40,600 --> 01:35:44,680
 But also for those who have suffered

1553
01:35:44,680 --> 01:35:49,600
 because of the heavy handedness of others

1554
01:35:49,600 --> 01:35:56,720
 is the need to express,

1555
01:35:57,680 --> 01:36:00,600
 the concern, the lament, the complaint

1556
01:36:00,600 --> 01:36:05,000
 in ways that can be heard.

1557
01:36:05,000 --> 01:36:09,320
 And that's difficult to do when you're hurting

1558
01:36:09,320 --> 01:36:13,680
 because if you're hurting you're not trying to argue,

1559
01:36:13,680 --> 01:36:16,880
 you're not trying to organize an argument

1560
01:36:16,880 --> 01:36:19,760
 to make rational sense.

1561
01:36:19,760 --> 01:36:25,240
 But that's the tension I think that we're in

1562
01:36:25,240 --> 01:36:30,240
 and sometimes it may be need to reach outside

1563
01:36:30,240 --> 01:36:35,560
 to find someone else that will have some mutual respect

1564
01:36:35,560 --> 01:36:42,240
 to be an interpreter and a mediator

1565
01:36:42,240 --> 01:36:46,600
 to help make some of that happen.

1566
01:36:46,600 --> 01:36:49,000
 It's difficult on big scales

1567
01:36:49,000 --> 01:36:50,720
 because when you got big scale stuff

1568
01:36:50,720 --> 01:36:52,880
 it gets really complicated with size

1569
01:36:52,880 --> 01:36:57,640
 and who speaks for whom and who is the interpreter

1570
01:36:57,640 --> 01:36:59,840
 and who's not at the table.

1571
01:36:59,840 --> 01:37:01,080
 And because it's complicated

1572
01:37:01,080 --> 01:37:02,680
 doesn't mean that it shouldn't be done.

1573
01:37:02,680 --> 01:37:04,440
 I just wanted to name that it is.

1574
01:37:04,440 --> 01:37:10,800
 But some need to repent of imposing their will.

1575
01:37:10,800 --> 01:37:20,440
 Some need to exercise their agency

1576
01:37:20,440 --> 01:37:24,600
 to name what they desire.

1577
01:37:24,600 --> 01:37:29,000
 And we probably also need to have some other partners

1578
01:37:29,000 --> 01:37:33,400
 to be a part of interpreting and mediating

1579
01:37:33,400 --> 01:37:36,000
 because it's difficult without that.

1580
01:37:36,000 --> 01:37:39,120
 If you're not used to listening to people

1581
01:37:39,120 --> 01:37:40,960
 it's very, very difficult.

1582
01:37:40,960 --> 01:37:48,160
 But more and more folks who have suffered

1583
01:37:48,160 --> 01:37:52,800
 the weight of that imposition, voices are rising up

1584
01:37:52,800 --> 01:37:56,360
 and then there are others who are being allies

1585
01:37:56,360 --> 01:38:01,360
 to try to help to advocate, to add voice

1586
01:38:01,360 --> 01:38:05,120
 to those whose voices have often not been heard.

1587
01:38:05,120 --> 01:38:09,840
 But I think it's gonna have to work on both sides

1588
01:38:09,840 --> 01:38:13,320
 and most people are not very good at that.

1589
01:38:13,320 --> 01:38:15,760
 And so it'll be messy.

1590
01:38:17,760 --> 01:38:21,800
 But we've been given a ministry of reconciliation

1591
01:38:21,800 --> 01:38:24,880
 which is messy because the cross is involved.

1592
01:38:24,880 --> 01:38:29,120
 But thanks for that important question.

1593
01:38:29,120 --> 01:38:33,560
 - All right, thank you.

1594
01:38:33,560 --> 01:38:34,720
 Any other questions?

1595
01:38:34,720 --> 01:38:38,760
 Yeah, go ahead, please.

1596
01:38:38,760 --> 01:38:43,400
 - May I change the topic a little bit

1597
01:38:43,400 --> 01:38:45,840
 still on the issue of leadership?

1598
01:38:45,840 --> 01:38:49,880
 One of the things I found among students

1599
01:38:49,880 --> 01:38:53,560
 or among the younger pastor in Hong Kong

1600
01:38:53,560 --> 01:38:56,920
 is many of them don't want to be leader.

1601
01:38:56,920 --> 01:38:58,720
 They don't want to be the senior pastor.

1602
01:38:58,720 --> 01:39:00,520
 They want to be associates pastor

1603
01:39:00,520 --> 01:39:02,560
 or assistant pastor or whatever.

1604
01:39:02,560 --> 01:39:04,720
 Part of the reason is because the society

1605
01:39:04,720 --> 01:39:07,560
 is getting more and more divisive.

1606
01:39:07,560 --> 01:39:11,480
 And being a leader, often you have to face

1607
01:39:11,480 --> 01:39:13,280
 a lot of criticism.

1608
01:39:13,280 --> 01:39:15,400
 Now there are leaders like Donald Trump

1609
01:39:15,400 --> 01:39:17,400
 who thrive in criticism.

1610
01:39:17,400 --> 01:39:20,760
 The more people criticize him, the more excited he get.

1611
01:39:20,760 --> 01:39:24,080
 And there are people who like people like Donald Trump

1612
01:39:24,080 --> 01:39:29,080
 who write dirty words in his Instagram.

1613
01:39:29,080 --> 01:39:30,560
 Some people like it.

1614
01:39:30,560 --> 01:39:34,080
 So I mean, our culture seems to be,

1615
01:39:34,080 --> 01:39:37,400
 who want to be a leader?

1616
01:39:37,400 --> 01:39:41,320
 It seems to be those people who need a big ego.

1617
01:39:41,320 --> 01:39:42,560
 Then they want to be a leader.

1618
01:39:42,560 --> 01:39:47,000
 Those people, you said humble and grope leadership.

1619
01:39:47,000 --> 01:39:48,400
 I will listen to my friend.

1620
01:39:48,400 --> 01:39:51,320
 If they say no, I will stop it.

1621
01:39:51,320 --> 01:39:53,680
 Those people, they don't want to be leader

1622
01:39:53,680 --> 01:39:57,200
 because being leader in the culture today

1623
01:39:57,200 --> 01:40:02,040
 is such a controversial thing to do.

1624
01:40:02,040 --> 01:40:07,040
 So how would you encourage the younger generation,

1625
01:40:07,040 --> 01:40:10,880
 people younger than me, how would you encourage them

1626
01:40:10,880 --> 01:40:13,680
 so that they would be willing

1627
01:40:13,680 --> 01:40:16,280
 or they would actually want to be a leader

1628
01:40:16,280 --> 01:40:19,320
 when they don't have an ego as big as Donald Trump?

1629
01:40:19,320 --> 01:40:25,160
 - Let's talk about pastoral.

1630
01:40:25,160 --> 01:40:28,520
 I think I was hearing you talk about pastoral leadership.

1631
01:40:28,520 --> 01:40:32,840
 And so I think that in the United States,

1632
01:40:32,840 --> 01:40:37,840
 one of the challenges that has been accumulating

1633
01:40:39,960 --> 01:40:43,040
 is a,

1634
01:40:43,040 --> 01:40:49,480
 and we live in a culture

1635
01:40:49,480 --> 01:40:55,240
 where negativity gets celebrated.

1636
01:40:55,240 --> 01:41:01,400
 The more negative you are, the more people cheer you.

1637
01:41:01,400 --> 01:41:04,200
 And I think that's what you have noted.

1638
01:41:06,480 --> 01:41:11,480
 And a part of our, I think our challenge is

1639
01:41:11,480 --> 01:41:15,480
 to tell people to grow up and stop that.

1640
01:41:15,480 --> 01:41:21,760
 But it also means that

1641
01:41:21,760 --> 01:41:27,280
 we need to elevate the positive models.

1642
01:41:27,280 --> 01:41:29,920
 So when I hear people say,

1643
01:41:29,920 --> 01:41:31,480
 oh, I never will want to be a pastor.

1644
01:41:31,480 --> 01:41:36,080
 I don't want to be the, I take personal offense to that.

1645
01:41:36,080 --> 01:41:39,680
 I mean, I'm not angry, but I take personal offense to it.

1646
01:41:39,680 --> 01:41:41,160
 My father was a pastor.

1647
01:41:41,160 --> 01:41:42,000
 I'm a pastor.

1648
01:41:42,000 --> 01:41:43,360
 I have a brother who's a pastor.

1649
01:41:43,360 --> 01:41:45,160
 It's a noble calling.

1650
01:41:45,160 --> 01:41:51,320
 You get the privilege of helping to shape

1651
01:41:51,320 --> 01:41:55,280
 the spiritual formation, the Christian discipleship

1652
01:41:55,280 --> 01:41:58,240
 of people who need to know the Lord

1653
01:41:58,240 --> 01:42:00,240
 and who can grow and flourish.

1654
01:42:00,240 --> 01:42:02,200
 Who wouldn't want to do that?

1655
01:42:05,080 --> 01:42:07,680
 See, a part of it is how we talk about it.

1656
01:42:07,680 --> 01:42:13,520
 So if we talk about, you're gonna be in the middle

1657
01:42:13,520 --> 01:42:16,440
 of a whole lot of conflict, well, who wants to do that?

1658
01:42:16,440 --> 01:42:19,400
 Hey, you get to curate a community

1659
01:42:19,400 --> 01:42:22,560
 to help people know what it means

1660
01:42:22,560 --> 01:42:25,280
 to live in the fullness of Christ Jesus.

1661
01:42:25,280 --> 01:42:29,000
 It's a privilege.

1662
01:42:29,000 --> 01:42:34,000
 You get to accompany people in the big challenges of life

1663
01:42:35,920 --> 01:42:40,920
 and birth and death and decision-making.

1664
01:42:40,920 --> 01:42:47,480
 And that's a privilege to walk along,

1665
01:42:47,480 --> 01:42:49,680
 to be invited into that space.

1666
01:42:49,680 --> 01:42:54,480
 But people often don't, at least in my context,

1667
01:42:54,480 --> 01:42:57,080
 they often don't talk about pastoral life like that.

1668
01:42:57,080 --> 01:42:59,960
 They talk about managing conflict

1669
01:42:59,960 --> 01:43:02,320
 and managing budgets and managing problems.

1670
01:43:03,920 --> 01:43:07,600
 But they don't talk about the joy and the privilege

1671
01:43:07,600 --> 01:43:12,040
 of being a companion on the journey.

1672
01:43:12,040 --> 01:43:17,040
 And I think that part of what institutions like this

1673
01:43:17,040 --> 01:43:20,880
 have an opportunity to do is to elevate

1674
01:43:20,880 --> 01:43:23,720
 what being a pastor is about.

1675
01:43:23,720 --> 01:43:29,440
 We acknowledge it comes with some other stuff,

1676
01:43:29,440 --> 01:43:33,160
 but it's not really, it's not about programs

1677
01:43:33,160 --> 01:43:37,480
 and projects and partisanship.

1678
01:43:37,480 --> 01:43:38,840
 That's not what it's about.

1679
01:43:38,840 --> 01:43:43,960
 That comes with it, but it's really about

1680
01:43:43,960 --> 01:43:48,840
 helping people to see Jesus.

1681
01:43:48,840 --> 01:43:49,960
 And if we can do that,

1682
01:43:49,960 --> 01:43:52,760
 that makes all the difference in the world.

1683
01:43:52,760 --> 01:43:54,920
 And it makes the other worth it.

1684
01:43:54,920 --> 01:43:58,800
 So I think that that's a part of it.

1685
01:43:58,800 --> 01:44:03,800
 And to start cultivating the kind of inner resolve,

1686
01:44:03,800 --> 01:44:09,560
 we do have to, we have to develop something like Teflon

1687
01:44:09,560 --> 01:44:18,200
 where nothing sticks to it, like a nonstick skillet.

1688
01:44:18,200 --> 01:44:22,160
 If you're gonna survive in this business,

1689
01:44:22,160 --> 01:44:27,160
 you have to get some Teflon and then grow a spine.

1690
01:44:29,640 --> 01:44:33,520
 And be able to look somebody in the eye and say,

1691
01:44:33,520 --> 01:44:34,880
 "You're wrong."

1692
01:44:34,880 --> 01:44:37,960
 You can keep saying it if you want to,

1693
01:44:37,960 --> 01:44:40,160
 and you can be wrong, you get the privilege of being wrong,

1694
01:44:40,160 --> 01:44:41,280
 but you're wrong.

1695
01:44:41,280 --> 01:44:48,200
 There is a book, it's probably 20 years old now,

1696
01:44:48,200 --> 01:44:53,640
 by an author called Don Miguel Ruiz, R-U-I-Z,

1697
01:44:55,360 --> 01:44:58,880
 called "The Four Agreements."

1698
01:44:58,880 --> 01:45:03,280
 And the logic is that all of us have agreements

1699
01:45:03,280 --> 01:45:06,160
 like principles that we live by.

1700
01:45:06,160 --> 01:45:07,160
 And when we're young,

1701
01:45:07,160 --> 01:45:11,920
 we live by somebody else's principles or agreements.

1702
01:45:11,920 --> 01:45:14,600
 But at some point you have to decide your own.

1703
01:45:14,600 --> 01:45:17,960
 I'm not sure I can remember all of them,

1704
01:45:17,960 --> 01:45:22,960
 but one is something like, "Do your best."

1705
01:45:23,720 --> 01:45:28,320
 And he uses an analogy of playing cards,

1706
01:45:28,320 --> 01:45:30,880
 like a game of cards, you know what I'm talking about?

1707
01:45:30,880 --> 01:45:31,720
 Okay.

1708
01:45:31,720 --> 01:45:36,720
 And he says that what you do is you play the best hand

1709
01:45:36,720 --> 01:45:40,120
 you dealt, stay in the game,

1710
01:45:40,120 --> 01:45:42,760
 and you're probably gonna get a better hand at cards.

1711
01:45:42,760 --> 01:45:45,960
 But just do your best, play the best hand you have.

1712
01:45:45,960 --> 01:45:48,360
 That's one example, agreement.

1713
01:45:48,360 --> 01:45:52,280
 Another one he says is, "Be impeccable with your word."

1714
01:45:52,280 --> 01:45:56,400
 And what he says is that the root for impeccable

1715
01:45:56,400 --> 01:45:58,760
 is without blemish.

1716
01:45:58,760 --> 01:46:01,440
 So don't say anything negative about yourself

1717
01:46:01,440 --> 01:46:03,560
 or about somebody else.

1718
01:46:03,560 --> 01:46:09,400
 The third one is, "Assume nothing, always get clarity."

1719
01:46:09,400 --> 01:46:13,160
 And the fourth one, and this is the one I was getting to,

1720
01:46:13,160 --> 01:46:14,880
 the one that has meant most for me

1721
01:46:14,880 --> 01:46:17,120
 is, "Take nothing personally."

1722
01:46:18,600 --> 01:46:23,240
 And he says, "I am not obligated to receive your poison.

1723
01:46:23,240 --> 01:46:24,880
 "The poison you spew out

1724
01:46:24,880 --> 01:46:27,440
 "is because the poison is in your heart.

1725
01:46:27,440 --> 01:46:29,800
 "I'm not obligated to take your poison."

1726
01:46:29,800 --> 01:46:34,680
 That has helped me for a generation.

1727
01:46:34,680 --> 01:46:38,280
 That when people spew poison at me,

1728
01:46:38,280 --> 01:46:40,840
 it's about the toxins in their lives.

1729
01:46:40,840 --> 01:46:42,600
 It had nothing to do with me.

1730
01:46:42,600 --> 01:46:44,200
 I'm not obligated to take that.

1731
01:46:45,280 --> 01:46:50,040
 And we have to develop tactics to keep our sanity

1732
01:46:50,040 --> 01:46:55,040
 when people come at us in ways that are toxic and noxious.

1733
01:46:55,040 --> 01:47:01,400
 Those are some of my contributions.

1734
01:47:01,400 --> 01:47:08,280
 - Yeah, I noticed the same thing

1735
01:47:08,280 --> 01:47:11,000
 that many of our young pastors,

1736
01:47:11,000 --> 01:47:15,520
 they don't want to be a sort of senior pastor in the church.

1737
01:47:15,520 --> 01:47:18,960
 In fact, I agree.

1738
01:47:18,960 --> 01:47:20,600
 (laughing)

1739
01:47:20,600 --> 01:47:25,600
 Why in your early years of ministry,

1740
01:47:25,600 --> 01:47:30,080
 you are so keen to be a senior pastor of the church?

1741
01:47:30,080 --> 01:47:35,120
 What I mean is that he has to learn,

1742
01:47:35,120 --> 01:47:38,480
 gain more experience in his pastoral ministry,

1743
01:47:38,480 --> 01:47:40,160
 in terms of preaching and teaching,

1744
01:47:40,160 --> 01:47:41,800
 in terms of pastoral care,

1745
01:47:41,800 --> 01:47:43,720
 in terms of training,

1746
01:47:43,720 --> 01:47:44,840
 in terms of discipling,

1747
01:47:44,840 --> 01:47:48,200
 or even do conflict resolving, all those stuff.

1748
01:47:48,200 --> 01:47:53,200
 So unless the person gain enough experience,

1749
01:47:53,200 --> 01:47:55,520
 and in the process of that,

1750
01:47:55,520 --> 01:48:00,520
 he gain confidence in doing leading,

1751
01:48:00,520 --> 01:48:06,360
 then by then, he might have more and more followers.

1752
01:48:09,560 --> 01:48:11,120
 People like to follow him.

1753
01:48:11,120 --> 01:48:16,120
 People like to come under him and to submit to him.

1754
01:48:16,120 --> 01:48:22,960
 Then by then, he become a leader,

1755
01:48:22,960 --> 01:48:25,760
 whether you like it or not.

1756
01:48:25,760 --> 01:48:29,840
 So what I mean is I come across a simple definition

1757
01:48:29,840 --> 01:48:30,760
 of a leader.

1758
01:48:30,760 --> 01:48:31,600
 What is a leader?

1759
01:48:31,600 --> 01:48:32,440
 Who is a leader?

1760
01:48:32,440 --> 01:48:35,040
 A leader is who has followers.

1761
01:48:35,040 --> 01:48:36,480
 If you don't have followers,

1762
01:48:36,480 --> 01:48:37,880
 this leader is not a leader.

1763
01:48:37,880 --> 01:48:40,800
 He's just a walker, all right?

1764
01:48:40,800 --> 01:48:43,680
 So that means, what it means,

1765
01:48:43,680 --> 01:48:46,600
 maybe I don't mind the person don't take,

1766
01:48:46,600 --> 01:48:50,720
 don't become a senior pastor yet for a few years.

1767
01:48:50,720 --> 01:48:52,720
 And then for a number of years,

1768
01:48:52,720 --> 01:48:55,120
 he gradually gain experience and confidence,

1769
01:48:55,120 --> 01:48:57,800
 and people like to, okay, come on.

1770
01:48:57,800 --> 01:49:01,840
 You become our leader.

1771
01:49:01,840 --> 01:49:06,000
 Then by then, you could become a leader.

1772
01:49:06,000 --> 01:49:09,440
 So what I mean is I don't want the person

1773
01:49:09,440 --> 01:49:11,200
 so keen to become a leader,

1774
01:49:11,200 --> 01:49:16,800
 but concentrate on your pastoral ministry first,

1775
01:49:16,800 --> 01:49:18,920
 and so on and so forth, all right?

1776
01:49:18,920 --> 01:49:20,880
 So my answer is to that.

1777
01:49:20,880 --> 01:49:24,000
 - I thought of one more thing,

1778
01:49:24,000 --> 01:49:28,840
 and that is that sometimes I think

1779
01:49:28,840 --> 01:49:32,200
 when people say, "I don't wanna be a pastor,"

1780
01:49:32,200 --> 01:49:34,240
 sometimes I think what they're doing

1781
01:49:34,240 --> 01:49:38,040
 is looking at models that they have seen

1782
01:49:38,040 --> 01:49:41,200
 and saying, "If that is what being a pastor is,

1783
01:49:41,200 --> 01:49:43,240
 "I don't want to be that."

1784
01:49:43,240 --> 01:49:47,400
 And I think that that's different

1785
01:49:47,400 --> 01:49:50,120
 from a description of a pastor

1786
01:49:50,120 --> 01:49:52,760
 in terms of a shepherd of the flock

1787
01:49:52,760 --> 01:49:55,720
 or someone who is leading a community

1788
01:49:55,720 --> 01:49:57,240
 to be more like Christ.

1789
01:49:57,240 --> 01:50:03,320
 I think that that's legitimate to say if that,

1790
01:50:03,320 --> 01:50:05,000
 especially like in the United States

1791
01:50:05,000 --> 01:50:10,000
 where you've had some really public examples,

1792
01:50:10,000 --> 01:50:11,920
 if that's all they've seen,

1793
01:50:11,920 --> 01:50:18,160
 lack of integrity, if that's what they've seen,

1794
01:50:18,160 --> 01:50:20,840
 I think that sometimes what they're saying

1795
01:50:20,840 --> 01:50:23,080
 is, "I don't wanna be that."

1796
01:50:23,080 --> 01:50:25,000
 I'm not sure that's the same thing as saying,

1797
01:50:25,000 --> 01:50:26,760
 "I don't wanna be a pastor,"

1798
01:50:26,760 --> 01:50:29,400
 because they're saying, "I wanna be a leader.

1799
01:50:29,400 --> 01:50:32,760
 "I wanna be a different kind of leader."

1800
01:50:32,760 --> 01:50:37,640
 And I think that there's been such a radical shift

1801
01:50:37,640 --> 01:50:42,080
 just in the last 25 years of culture

1802
01:50:42,080 --> 01:50:48,320
 that perhaps the 50 years leading up to that

1803
01:50:48,320 --> 01:50:53,440
 has been more of that's a kind of stagnant model,

1804
01:50:53,440 --> 01:50:56,040
 but now there's been so much different

1805
01:50:59,520 --> 01:51:03,880
 in terms of the last quarter century of changes in the world.

1806
01:51:03,880 --> 01:51:05,960
 So maybe what our task is

1807
01:51:05,960 --> 01:51:09,560
 is to give a better definition of what a pastor is

1808
01:51:09,560 --> 01:51:13,440
 rather than saying, "Look at him or look at her,"

1809
01:51:13,440 --> 01:51:15,640
 and say, "That's what a pastor is,"

1810
01:51:15,640 --> 01:51:18,760
 so that we give people encouragement

1811
01:51:18,760 --> 01:51:23,760
 to describe what a pastor is with the key functions,

1812
01:51:26,160 --> 01:51:30,880
 with maturity and experience and that kind of stuff.

1813
01:51:30,880 --> 01:51:33,960
 But even at that, the organizations

1814
01:51:33,960 --> 01:51:37,280
 that have the responsibility of blessing people

1815
01:51:37,280 --> 01:51:39,840
 and saying, "You're ready now,"

1816
01:51:39,840 --> 01:51:43,760
 may be challenged to update our evaluation,

1817
01:51:43,760 --> 01:51:48,880
 because if what we're doing is looking backwards

1818
01:51:48,880 --> 01:51:51,960
 into the 20th century,

1819
01:51:51,960 --> 01:51:54,920
 we can't talk about 21st century leaders now,

1820
01:51:54,920 --> 01:51:58,920
 because we're starting the second quarter

1821
01:51:58,920 --> 01:52:01,000
 of the 21st century.

1822
01:52:01,000 --> 01:52:05,560
 So to act like the 21st century is new is backwards.

1823
01:52:05,560 --> 01:52:07,760
 I mean, there are adults, young adults,

1824
01:52:07,760 --> 01:52:10,440
 who were not alive for Y2K.

1825
01:52:10,440 --> 01:52:12,640
 You all remember when people were worried

1826
01:52:12,640 --> 01:52:14,960
 about are the computers going off,

1827
01:52:14,960 --> 01:52:18,080
 are planes going to fly, drop out of the air,

1828
01:52:18,080 --> 01:52:20,600
 and are we going to lose all of our money in the bank?

1829
01:52:20,600 --> 01:52:25,360
 There are young adults who have no clue what Y2K was.

1830
01:52:25,360 --> 01:52:32,320
 So we're on the second quarter of the 21st century

1831
01:52:32,320 --> 01:52:34,560
 with all kinds of developments.

1832
01:52:34,560 --> 01:52:36,680
 I mean, we came through the pandemic,

1833
01:52:36,680 --> 01:52:37,920
 and we're still trying to figure out

1834
01:52:37,920 --> 01:52:39,600
 what post-pandemic lives.

1835
01:52:39,600 --> 01:52:42,120
 You talked about AI earlier.

1836
01:52:42,120 --> 01:52:45,400
 We got a different kind of global politics going on,

1837
01:52:45,400 --> 01:52:47,800
 a rise of nationalism,

1838
01:52:47,800 --> 01:52:51,240
 but segmentation is different.

1839
01:52:51,240 --> 01:52:56,240
 So it may be what they're seeing as pastor

1840
01:52:56,240 --> 01:52:59,560
 may be what they're rejecting,

1841
01:52:59,560 --> 01:53:04,000
 rather than what a biblical model is,

1842
01:53:04,000 --> 01:53:05,720
 is to feed my sheep.

1843
01:53:05,720 --> 01:53:09,320
 That might be one of our tasks

1844
01:53:09,320 --> 01:53:12,120
 about helping to rehabilitate

1845
01:53:12,120 --> 01:53:16,600
 what the image of a pastor is,

1846
01:53:16,600 --> 01:53:20,360
 and encouraging people to live into that calling.

1847
01:53:20,360 --> 01:53:25,960
 - Thank you very much for your response.

1848
01:53:25,960 --> 01:53:29,200
 And I guess it is nearly time for us to end.

1849
01:53:29,200 --> 01:53:32,560
 And I guess the comment that Dr. Goldie made

1850
01:53:32,560 --> 01:53:35,120
 makes a perfect conclusion to the leadership.

1851
01:53:35,120 --> 01:53:37,840
 You know, it's looking forward

1852
01:53:37,840 --> 01:53:41,480
 and also pointing to some good model.

1853
01:53:41,480 --> 01:53:46,000
 And may God help us that we become one of those, hopefully.

1854
01:53:46,000 --> 01:53:50,480
 So let's join me to give a big hand to Dr. Goldie

1855
01:53:50,480 --> 01:53:51,680
 for this wonderful lecture,

1856
01:53:51,680 --> 01:53:53,840
 and Dr. Spak Hein is back with us.

1857
01:53:53,840 --> 01:53:58,600
 And also this concludes the lecture tonight.

1858
01:53:58,600 --> 01:54:01,960
 And so good evening, everybody, and God bless you.

1859
01:54:01,960 --> 01:54:02,800
 Thank you.

1860
01:54:02,800 --> 01:54:05,360
 (upbeat music)

